<SLUG> BC-Japan-Peacekeeping </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Japan considers wider U.N. peacekeeping role for troops
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The government is considering allowing Japanese
troops to give wider logistical support to U.N. peacekeeping
missions, newspapers reported Saturday.
	   The Japanese constitution, written by the U.S. occupation
authorities after World War II, limits the Japanese military to
self-defense, and Tokyo has allowed its troops only restricted
involvement in U.N. missions.
	   But the ruling Liberal Democratic Party is being forced to come
up with a wider policy as a condition for a coalition government
with the opposition Liberal Party, the Asahi and Yomiuri newspapers
reported.
	   The Foreign Ministry is working on a proposal setting new
guidelines for Japanese involvement in medical, transportation and
other support for U.N. peacekeepers, but away from combat zones,
the newspapers said, citing unidentified government sources.
	   The head of the Liberal Party, Ichiro Ozawa, is pushing the
government to change its interpretation of the constitution to
allow Japanese soldiers to join any U.N. backed military
operations, such as the 1991 Gulf War to drive Iraq out of Kuwait.
	   But the Asahi newspaper said the government opposes that,
arguing that the constitution bans any operations abroad that
involve combat, the newspaper said.
	   Under current policy, the Japanese military's involvement in
U.N. peacekeeping is limited to noncombat observer missions, such
as monitoring the implementation of truce agreements.
	   (jc) 	   
</TEXT>
