<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-New Zealand-India, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Doull grabs seven for NZ
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with stumps score
 &UR; By IHITHISHAM KAMARDEEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) _ New Zealand paceman Simon Doull
destroyed India's batting with seven wickets Saturday as the hosts
reached a good position on the opening day of the second test.
	   Indian captain Mohammad Azharuddin scored a classy unbeaten 103
to carry India to 208 all out after he won the toss. New Zealand
was 51 for one at stumps.
	   Doull claimed a career-best 7-65 to make a mockery of the much
vaunted Indian top order while Azharuddin tried to wrest the
initiative with his century on a difficult pitch offering plenty of
sideways movement.
	   New Zealand lost Matthew Bell for four in his first test, but
Matthew Horne and skipper Stephen Fleming took New Zealand to
stumps with 16 and 27 respectively.
	   After the first test in Dunedin had been abandoned without a
ball bowled, India's batting first was soon in trouble against the
seam and swing of Doull.
	   Doull, who had been doubtful for the test after withdrawing with
an injured calf muscle before the first test, grabbed the first
seven wickets to fall running into the wind from the pavilion end
at the Basin Reserve.
	   Exploiting the early dampness, Doull had India teetering on 16
for four in the first hour.
	   India enjoyed a brief reprieve during a forceful 82-run stand
for the fifth wicket between Sachin Tendulkar (47) and Azharuddin,
but Doull's spell after lunch further buried the visitors' hopes.
	   Doull followed up his 4-7 in 27 balls before lunch with 3-9 in
24 balls after the break as India stumbled to 149 for eight.
	   Doull then had 7-34 leaving Azharuddin unbeaten on 60 and the
tail to bat with.
	   Azharuddin playing in his 93rd test rose to the challenge and
put the three-pronged seam attack to sword, cutting and driving
furiously for most of his 14 boundaries.
	   It was a typical captain's innings by the 35-year old veteran.
After Anil Kumble had helped him add 33 runs for the seventh
wicket, Azharuddin found an unlikely partner in No.10 Venkatesh
Prasad and hammered 58 runs for the ninth wicket.
	   Prasad was equal to the task and defied the Black Caps for 62
minutes for a career-best 15.
	   Azharuddin, whose first two scoring shots were boundaries, raced
to his 21st century in 210 minutes. His second fifty came off just
60 balls as he made only his ninth century in 51 tests outside
India.
	   The only blemish in Azharuddin's 230-minute stay at the crease
was when he was dropped off an attempted hook by wicketkeeper Adam
Parore off part-time medium paceman Craig McMillan on 103.
	   The last four wickets helped the skipper add an invaluable 109
after Tendulkar's dismissal had India struggling on 99 for five.
	   Before lunch Azharuddin and Tendulkar treated a 9,000-plus
Boxing Day crowd to some exhilarating batting as they repaired the
early damage done by Doull.
	   After a slow start a quite start, Tendulkar made his presence
felt with a mind boggling 72-ball innings that produced 47 runs.
	   His innings was cut short by Doull in the third over after lunch
when the right hand flicked a catch to Bell at square leg.
	   Both teams went into the test with two spinners each. New
Zealand picked off-spinner Paul Wiseman and India included teenage
off-spinner Harbhajan Singh to partner leg-spinner Anil Kumble.
	    &UR; (ik-tjh)
</TEXT>
