w1666 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Yachting-Sydne     12-26 0328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Yachting-Sydney-Hobart </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Favorites stage early duel
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Race favorites Sayonara and Brindabella
staged an early duel at the start of Saturday's Sydney-to-Hobart
yacht race, although the American maxi suffered a setback after it
was first out of Sydney Heads.
	   Sayonara, the world maxi champion, led at the first marker but
lost her first spinnaker shortly after passing through the heads
out of Sydney Harbor.
	   However, its crew of top class international sailors had a
replacement up within seconds.
	   The setback allowed Brindabella, last year's line honors winner,
to draw level with Sayonara after the latter bolted clear following
a strong start.
	   There was excitement at the start when Nokia, the biggest boat
in the 115-strong fleet, collided with Bright Morning Star. The
83-foot maxi ketch did not appear to have the right of way.
	   Early placings followed the favored list with Australian maxi
Wild Thing third out of the heads.
	   Another maxi, Marchioness, was fourth, followed by the 60-footer
Sydney.
	   A huge but well-behaved spectator fleet containing thousands of
onlookers gathered to see the entrants embark upon their
630-nautical mile sail south and across to Hobart on the island
state of Tasmania.
	   Sayonara, the 1995 line honors winner, was rated a strong
favorite, with Brindabella, Wild Thing and Nokia the only other
boats attracting interest in the battle to reach Hobart first.
	   The leading maxis maintained a strong early pace courtesy of
favorable 10 to 15 knot northeasterly breezes.
	   While the front-runners were easily exceeding the 10- to 11-knot
pace needed to eclipse Morning Glory's 1996 race record, the fleet
was anticipating much tougher conditions later in the day.
	   Morning Glory, a German maxi, broke the 21-year-old race record
two years ago, arriving in Hobart two days, 14 hours, seven minutes
and 10 seconds after she left Sydney. (djp) 	   
</TEXT>
