w1688 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Cricket-Azharu     12-26 0303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Azharuddin </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Azhar defends his decision to bat first
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Sports-Cricket-New Zealand-India
 &UR; By IHITHISHAM KAMARDEEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) _ Skipper Mohammad Azharuddin
defended his decision to bat first after his century saved the day
for India in the second cricket test at Basin Reserve Saturday.
	   Swing bowler Simon Doull cut through the strong Indian batting
line up with a career-best 7-65 as India was dismissed for 208 on
the first day.
	   Azharuddin's 21st century rescued the side after Doull's initial
eight-over burst had reduced the innings to 16 for four in the
first hour.
	   ``The wicket did a bit in the first hour and a half,''
Azharuddin said. ``I give credit to Simon who bowled very well.
	   ``I think when you bowl like that there isn't much one could do.
No complaints. They all got out to good balls.''
	   Azharuddin said it was easier to bat after lunch but had plenty
of praise for Doull.
	   ``You can't take away the performance of Simon,'' Azharuddin
said. ``It was a tremendous effort. He bowled an outstanding line
and length.''
	   Azharuddin said he did the right thing by batting first after
India had opted for two spinners.
	   ``The spinners are our strength and we have to play
accordingly,'' he said.
	   Doull, a doubtful starter 48 hours before the test, said he had
an obligation to come out strongly after skipper Stephen Fleming
had lost the toss.
	   ``The onus was on the three seamers and it happened to be my
day,'' Doull said.
	   ``It was one of those days you felt good, had the rhythm and the
ball came out nicely out of the hand. The ball did lot more through
the air than off it, but I think there is plenty for the spinners
from day three onwards.''
 &UR; (ik-tjh)
</TEXT>
