<DATE_TIME> 12/26/1998 01:25:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1697 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cambodia-KhmerRouge 3rdLd-Writethru   12-26 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Khmer Rouge, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Top Khmer Rouge leaders defect to government; Ta Mok still at
</HEADLINE>
large &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS and UPDATES with details from defectors' letters, no
comment from U.S., U.N. officials, details &QL; 
 &UR; By KER MUNTHIT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Two key leaders in the Khmer Rouge's
reign of terror in Cambodia the 1970s defected to the government on
Saturday and declared they want to become ``ordinary citizens.''
	   The move by Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea _ in an apparent deal to
escape prosecution for crimes against humanity _ leaves only one
major Khmer Rouge figure at large, the brutal general Ta Mok.
	   The two defectors, who have surfaced in the former rebel town of
Pailin in Cambodia's rugged northwest, sent letters to Prime
Minister Hun Sen announcing they had broken away from Ta Mok.
	   ``I have no other request except a request to be allowed to live
as a simple citizen,'' Khieu Samphan wrote in a copy of his letter
obtained by The Associated Press. Nuon Chea also asked to return as
``an ordinary citizen.''
	   The letters indicated the pair had sealed their defection in
talks by telephone Friday night with Hun Sen. In a letter to King
Norodom Sihanouk read over national radio Saturday, Hun Sen praised
the move.
	   ``I would like to warmly welcome the two personalities and I
hope this decision made by the two personalities will become a
mobilization of strength for national reconstruction and peace,''
Hun Sen wrote.
	   Khieu Samphan was the the nominal Khmer Rouge leader, while Nuon
Chea was the rebel movement's political chief.
	   The two were considered among the main architects of the Khmer
Rouge's genocidal rule over Cambodia between 1975 and 1979. As many
as 2 million people died of starvation, disease and executions when
the Maoist guerrillas forced the population into massive
agricultural labor camps.
	   The Cambodian government and the United States have said in the
past that they wanted Khieu Samphan, Nuon Chea and Ta Mok captured
and tried for genocide and crimes against humanity.
	   A team of legal experts appointed by the United Nations visited
Cambodia last month to assess evidence for a possible international
tribunal. Hun Sen's spokesman, Prak Sokhon, said at the time that
the government remained committed to bringing them to trial.
	   The U.S. Embassy did not immediately take calls from reporters
seeking comment. Local United Nations staff said the only official
with the authority to speak was out of the country.
	   It was unclear whether the defection meant the Cambodian
government would not pursue charges against them, though Hun Sen's
language was notably conciliatory and mirrored that used in other
defections of equally bloodstained leaders.
	   Under the policy, no Khmer Rouge senior leader has ever been
taken into custody and tried.
	   Pailin, the town where the two defectors are, is under the
control of Ieng Sary, another top Khmer Rouge leader who negotiated
amnesty with the government in 1996 in exchange for leading
thousands of guerrillas out of combat.
	   Those defections marked the beginning of the end of a guerrilla
war that had festered since an invasion by Vietnam toppled the
Khmer Rouge regime in 1979.
	   The latest offer of defection comes just weeks after Khmer Rouge
chief of staff Khem Ngun and seven other generals surrendered and
returned to the Cambodian capital Phnom Penh for the first time in
19 years to meet government officials.
	   That surrender dealt what amounted to the final death blow to
the last hard-line faction.
	   Still at large is Ta Mok, the one-legged general known as ``The
Butcher'' for his revolutionary brutality. He seized command of
what remained of the hard-liners after deposing Pol Pot, the
long-time Khmer Rouge leader, in a bloody internal struggle in
1997.
	   Pol Pot, under house arrest by his former comrades, died of a
heart attack in April.
	   Ta Mok's violent reputation may make it difficult for the
government to avoid calls to have him tried _ either in Cambodia or
by an international court _ for crimes against humanity.
	   Nuon Chea is one of the most shadowy leaders of the group,
renowned for secrecy and paranoia. He was considered Pol Pot's No.
2 and a key political theorist.
	   Khieu Samphan was long the group's nominal leader, though real
power rested with Pol Pot and Ta Mok. Considered an intellectual,
he was the group's chief diplomat.
	   After Pol Pot's death, some observers believed Khieu Samphan was
being held against his will by Ta Mok, whom he feared.
</TEXT>
