<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Proposal for national talks involving Suharto founders
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ A controversial proposal for a
dialogue on Indonesia's social and political problems that would
include former President Suharto is foundering.
	   The idea was launched by Muslim leader Abdurrahman Wahid, who
believes Suharto remains a powerful figure even though he was
ousted in May after 32 years of authoritarian rule.
	   Last week, Wahid met Suharto and asked him to join a four-person
meeting on how to help Indonesia overcome political uncertainty,
social unrest and the worst economic crisis in three decades.
	   The other two participants were to be President B.J. Habibie,
Suharto's successor and onetime protege, and Gen. Wiranto, chief of
the politically powerful military.
	   However, The Jakarta Post on Saturday quoted Wahid as saying
Suharto was probably not interested in the proposal although he had
expressed enthusiasm for the idea.
	   ``I doubt that (Suharto) really wants to meet with Habibie. Let
us hope he was not talking nonsense,'' said Wahid, who is chairman
of Nahdlatul Ulama, Indonesia's biggest Muslim group.
	   Habibie, who has tried to distance himself from Suharto, has
shown little interest in Wahid's proposal. He is implementing
political reforms and has scheduled parliamentary elections in
June, but student protesters say he is not sincere about democratic
change.
	   Critics have expressed concern about any dialogue involving
Suharto, who faces demands from student activists that he be put on
trial on charges of corruption and human rights abuses.
	   Opponents have also suggested Wahid, who is considered a
possible presidential candidate in elections next year, proposed
the idea in order to gain a higher national profile.
	   Wahid has said that Suharto remains a key figure because he
likely still commands the loyalty of many government bureaucrats as
well as high-ranking military officials.
	   In recent months, Indonesia has endured outbursts of religious
and ethnic violence as well as persistent student protests against
Habibie.
</TEXT>
