<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-China-Crime Boss </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Chinese authorities commend officers for crime boss case
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Chinese authorities have commended police and
security agents for helping catch recently executed Hong Kong crime
boss Cheung ``Big Spender'' Tze-keung, a newspaper reported
Saturday.
	   Central and Guangdong provincial public security authorities
honored 11 units and 192 police in a ceremony attended by more than
1,200 people Friday, Chinese-language daily Ming Pao reported.
	   Cheung, 43, and four of his underlings were executed by gunfire
earlier this month in the southern Chinese city of Guangzhou
immediately after a court rejected their appeals in a sensational
gang trial.
	   The court had sentenced them to death last month for kidnapping
two Hong Kong tycoons, smuggling dynamite and guns from China into
Hong Kong, robbing gold stores, and stealing 277 tons of steel.
	   The kidnappings, reportedly of Victor Li, son of property
magnate Li Ka-shing, and Walter Kwok, chairman of big developer Sun
Hung Kai Properties, allegedly netted 1.6 billion Hong Kong dollars
(U.S. dlrs 210 million), the largest modern-day ransom.
	   Friday's ceremony included officials from Beijing and several
neighboring cities, with two police officers receiving
commendations of ``Second-class Model Hero,'' the paper reported.
	   Officials also handed out monetary awards between 200-600 yuan
(U.S. dlrs 24-72).
</TEXT>
