<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Panama Canal-Tourism,0377 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Panama hopes to turn canal into world's premier ecotourism resort
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: This story accompanies FEA-Panama Canal which moved in
previous cycle &QL; 
 &UR; With FEA-Panama Canal &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos NY197 &QL; 
 &UR; By JUAN ZAMORANO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GAMBOA, Panama (AP) _ Three abandoned single-story wooden houses
sit in the middle of the rainforest along the Chagres River, alone
but for the thousands of birds that screetch overhead.
	   It is here that a consortium is spending dlrs 25 million to
build a five-star hotel and resort, complete with 100 rooms, a
swimming pool, a convention center and a cable car to take tourists
on a half-mile (800-meter) journey above the canopy of virgin
rainforest.
	   And it is projects like this that the government hopes will more
than make up for the dlrs 300 million a year that the economy will
lose when the U.S. Army withdraws from the Panama Canal next year.
	   ``Panama has a tremendous advantage with all its forests. Here,
it's easy to build tourism,'' said Bernard Josephs, an English
businessman who is investing in a tourism project along the canal.
	   Panama is hoping that a major part of its new economy will be
ecotourism _ resorts that respect and profit from the untouched
nature that surrounds the 50-mile (80-kilometer) canal.
	   The Soberania Park nature reserve has more species of birds and
insects than the United States and Canada combined.
	   Near that park, one project is already up and running.
	   On a dock on Gatun Lake, which feeds the canal, a cruise ship
docks every Thursday. About 1,000 tourists _ mostly Americans _ get
off the ship to feast their eyes on the unspoiled rainforest.
	   Some take a helicopter ride over the rainforest. Some board a
smaller boat to sail the Chagres. Some swim in the lake. Some go to
the nearby canal locks to watch the ships raised and lowered. And
some visit nearby San Lorenzo Fort, a three-century-old castle.
	   ``I'm very impressed by the forest,'' said Lenor Chavez of
Albuquerque, New Mexico, eating a hamburger at the dock after a
trip to the fort and a swim in the lake. ``I'll never forget that I
swam in the canal. I'd like to come back to get to know the rest.''
</TEXT>
