<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Copper Strike-Christmas, 1st Ld-Writethru,0452 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Christmas comes to children despite copper strike _ thanks to
</HEADLINE>
`Art' &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with toys distributed to children. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   CANANEA, Mexico (AP) _ Despite a month-long strike that cut into
this copper-mining town's Christmas, there were boxes and boxes of
gifts for the children _ a present from an anonymous American.
	   Cabbage Patch dolls, soccer balls and footballs, Lego sets,
motorized cars and trucks _ union workers unloaded the gifts from a
fruit truck for a noon celebration Christmas Day.
	   A Tucson real estate man who identified himself only as Art but
said he once was a copper miner spent nearly dlrs 10,000 to provide
the 920 gifts. He explained he sympathized with the mining
families' plight and felt that as a Christian, helping the children
was the right thing to do.
	   The Barbie doll handed to Maria Jesus Verdugo was the only gift
she would get _ but it was enough.
	   ``She's beautiful,'' Maria murmured. ``I've been hoping for one
for a long time.''
	   With about 2,000 mine workers in their 36th day of a strike
protesting worker dismissals and other mine policies, Maria's
father could not even buy tamales and menudo for the family's
Christmas Eve dinner. They ate beans.
	   ``It's sad because they didn't stop the strike,'' said Maria.
``I was hoping they were going to end it before Christmas.''
	   Others echoed her comment.
	   ``I just want it to end so my dad is working again and can bring
money home,'' said Daniela Anahy Gonzalez, 10.
	   Patricia Ayala de Dorantes had sent her four children to bed
early Christmas Eve, not wanting to give them false hopes about
gifts.
	   ``You feel really ugly inside,'' she said. ``It's hard to know
what to say when they ask, `Mommy _ what about Santa Claus?' You
don't want to hurt them. You want to do everything possible to give
them the illusion of Santa Claus.''
	   Early Christmas Day, workers unloaded the truck, placing the
mounds of toys on a stage in a dusty old theater. Early that
afternoon, the toys were handed out as, one by one, children
scrambled up the stairs to the stage and held out their hands.
	   Martin Quintana was handed an American football. Clearly more
familiar with soccer balls, Martin seemed determined to get the
most out his new possession.
	   ``I have to learn how to use it,'' he said. ``I've got some
cousins on the other (U.S.) side who know and they can teach me.''
	   Martin's mother, Maria Luisa Quintana, said she had a message
for ``Senor Art.''
	   ``Tell him _ from all of us _ that we are very grateful for what
he did for our children,'' she said. ``God bless him.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Mexico-Copper Strike-Christmas, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
