</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Prison Disturbance, 1st Ld-Writethru,0322 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Armed inmates hold hostages in Mexican prison
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with quotes from city director of prisons, television
interviews with prisoner, hostage; reports that inmates have
grenades, hostages kept in infirmary. SUBS lead to reflect as few
as four inmates may have been involved. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo MO101 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Inmates overpowered guards and seized about
12 hostages at a prison packed with Christmas visitors, authorities
said.
	   Details of the disturbance at the Reclusorio Sur were not
immediately clear. News reports had said as many as 10 inmates were
involved, but Jaime Alvarez Ramos, the city's director of prisons,
said there were just four.
	   Alvarez told reporters the inmates started a riot on Friday to
give them an opportunity to escape. When that failed, they took
hostages.
	   One prisoner told the Televisa television network by telephone
that they had guns and grenades and would kill the hostages if the
police did not back away. An unidentified hostage told Televisa
they were being held in the infirmary and that one hostage was
injured.
	   Among the hostages were prison doctors and nurses, said Luis
Alberto Silva, a Red Cross official. It was not known if visitors
were among the hostages.
	   The government news agency Notimex, citing unofficial sources,
said two people had been killed, but Alvarez said there were no
deaths and only one person inside the prison had been injured.
Silva said eight people had been treated for minor injuries in the
distrubance.
	   Some 350 adults and children who had been visiting the prison
were evacuated after the hostages were taken, Notimex reported.
Most had swollen and teary eyes because of tear gas used by the
police, Notimex said.
	   More than 600 police surrounded the prison Friday evening,
Notimex said. But the standoff continued into the night.
</TEXT>
