w1755 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-EastTimor     12-26 0306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-East Timor </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
East Timor's spiritual leader unwilling to meet Indonesian
</HEADLINE>
president

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ East Timor's spiritual leader has
rejected an offer to meet President B.J. Habibie, citing
differences over Indonesian government policy in the former
Portuguese colony.
	   Earlier this week, Habibie said he wanted to meet Roman Catholic
Bishop Carlos Belo to discuss efforts to make peace in the troubled
territory, which was invaded by Indonesia in 1975.
	   However, Belo said the government has failed to respond to a
list of conditions that he submitted to Habibie during a meeting in
June, one month after the ouster of authoritarian President
Suharto.
	   ``If they're not carried out, I will not come to Jakarta,'' Belo
said Friday after celebrating Christmas at his home in Dili, the
capital of East Timor.
	   Belo, co-winner of the 1996 Nobel peace prize, did not specify
his conditions. But he has appealed for a reduction in the number
of Indonesian soldiers in East Timor as well as greater freedom of
movement for its inhabitants.
	   Belo also said it was not his role to brief Habibie on
developments in East Timor, which has endured fighting between the
military and separatist guerrillas for two decades.
	   ``I am not in a position to report about East Timor since it is
the job of the governor,'' Belo told reporters.
	   Indonesia has taken a more conciliatory stand on East Timor, and
talks on how to end the conflict in the half-island territory of
800,000 people have gained ground in recent months.
	   Indonesia has offered East Timor autonomy in exchange for
international recognition of its sovereignty. Independence
activists, however, say any autonomy deal must be transitional and
that a vote on self-determination must eventually take place.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
