<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Tonga-Cyclone, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cyclone Cora batters Pacific islands
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with cyclone moving away from Tonga &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) _ A fishing boat with six people on
board was missing Saturday after Cyclone Cora battered the Pacific
island nation of Tonga, Tongan police said.
	   The 7-meter (yard) boat was missing in high seas off the central
Ha'apai group of islands.
	   The cyclone, which had moved away from Tonga's main island
Tongatapu by 6 p.m. local time (0400 GMT), was reported to have
damaged crops and buildings and cut communications lines throughout
the island group.
	   The cyclone battered the main island of Tongatapu and the
Ha'apai chain with wind gusts of up to 100 mph (160 kph), a police
spokesman said.
	   ``We've had extensive damage ... to crops, especially
breadfruit, bananas and food crops, both in the northern islands
and now the central island of Tongatapu,'' the unidentified
spokesman told New Zealand's National Radio.
	   He said people had moved away from low-lying regions to avoid
the storm.
	   New Zealand Meteorological Service spokesman Chris Webster said
the worst of the storm appeared to be over.
	   He said the cyclone was now to east of Tongatapu and moving in a
southeasterly direction toward open sea.
	   The only remaining danger was to shipping in the area, he said.
</TEXT>
