w1764 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Taiwan-Cambodia-Waste     12-26 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Cambodia-Waste Scandal </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taiwan blames Cambodia for rejecting offer to resolve waste dispute
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ Taiwan criticized Cambodia on Saturday for
seeking China's approval before asking Taiwan to take back over
3,000 tons of mercury-tainted waste dumped by a Taiwanese firm, the
state-run news agency reported.
	   Five deaths have been blamed on the waste, sent to Cambodia last
month by Taiwan's giant Formosa Plastics Corp. It also led to the
panic-stricken exodus of residents from the Sihanoukville seaport
area where it was found two weeks ago.
	   Taiwan's Central News Agency quoted Foreign Ministry official Yu
Sheng-teh as saying Cambodia should not have unilaterally announced
an initial test result of the toxic content of the waste without
consulting Taiwan.
	   While rejecting a Taiwanese offer to send an official team to
investigate on the waste, Cambodian authorities sought help from
China to resolve the dispute, Yu said.
	   ``The inappropriate act has caused damage to our international
image,'' Yu was quoted as saying. ``It has also hurt our national
prestige.''
	   Yu did not elaborate. But Taiwanese newspapers reported earlier
that Cambodia consulted China on handling the waste and China
approved its request to return it to Taiwan.
	   Cambodia recognizes Beijing, which claims sovereignty over
Taiwan.
	   Taiwanese environmentalists have criticized the Taiwan
government for failing to seek a quick solution to the dispute and
to clean up Taiwan's image as an exporter of toxic waste.
	   Meanwhile, Taiwan's Environmental Protection Bureau asked
Formosa Plastics Corp. to send a delegation to Cambodia this week
to collect waste samples and conduct its own tests. It also asked
the company to take back the waste regardless of the test results.
	   Lee Chih-chun, the company's general manager, said it is willing
to abide by the government decision but he questioned the test
result announced by Cambodia that shows the waste has a mercury
content of 675 parts per million.
	   He said the waste, with a mercury content as low as 0.096 parts
per million, is not hazardous to human beings.
	   The waste, believed to be compressed industrial ash, was quietly
dumped near Sihanoukville last month.
	   A dock worker died a few days after cleaning the hold of the
ship that transported the waste, sparking riots in Sihanoukville.
	   Thousands have fled in fear of the waste and violent protests.
Police said four people were killed in traffic accidents on the
road to the capital.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
