<HEADER>
w1767 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BalloonQuest 1stLd-Writethru   12-26 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Balloon Quest, 1st Ld-Writethru,0658 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Balloonists ditch in the Pacific, ending round-the-world quest
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS and tightens; ADDS details on round-the-world balloon
launch scheduled for next week. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos WXS101, 105, 107, 108 &QL; 
 &UR; By BRUCE DUNFORD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HONOLULU (AP) _ After three failed attempts this year to float
around the world in a balloon, American millionaire Steve Fossett
sounded a little discouraged.
	   ``I think it's time to go sailing,'' Fossett said Friday after
he and two other adventurers abandoned their effort to make the
first nonstop around-the-world balloon flight.
	   British mogul Richard Branson, however, said he was undeterred.
	   ``We've finally cracked everything in the technology,'' he said.
``We'll buck up ourselves and start again.''
	   Fossett, Branson, and Per Lindstrand of Sweden, who have made a
total of 11 attempts at a nonstop flight around globe, were in good
condition when U.S. Coast Guard helicopters lifted them out of the
Pacific Ocean about 10 miles (16 kilometers) off Kahuku Point at
the northeast tip of Oahu.
	   ``We're glad to be alive,'' Branson said. ``We thought we were
going to make it all the way, but we hit a brick wall of bad
weather.''
	   They were seven days into their journey _ about the halfway
point _ when they ditched. The 272-foot-high (83-meter),
combination helium and hot-air balloon bounced for miles
(kilometers) in 3- to 4-foot (1- to 1.3-meter) seas because bolts
that were supposed to cut the balloon loose from the crew capsule
had been frozen by the cold and didn't work, Fossett said.
	   Fossett, who was forced to ditch in the Pacific during an
attempt to circle the globe earlier this year, described the
landing as ``pretty smooth,'' despite the bouncing.
	   His colleague Lindstrand begged to differ: ``This was the worst.
It was horrendous.''
	   The men lost the high-altitude 200 mph (320 kph) winds they
needed to carry them across the Pacific to North America. They got
caught in a low-pressure system and feared they would be stuck in
the trough for a week.
	   ``In the middle of the night we decided it was a hopeless
situation,'' Fossett said. ``If we had kept going, it would have
left us too far away from land for an easy pickup.''
	   They maneuvered the craft up and down between 6,000 feet (1,800
meters) and 27,000 feet (8,100 meters) to try to find a fast
easterly wind, but the best they could find was a 16 mph (26 kph)
breeze.
	   The system ``caught us very much by surprise. We thought we had
a solid route across the Pacific,'' Fossett said.
	   Balloon pilots aren't able to steer or control speed with much
precision. They navigate by changing the lift of the balloon to
ascend or descend into different wind currents.
	   Had the balloonists made the U.S. West Coast, they would have
broken the 15,200-mile (24,320-kilometer) balloon distance record
that Fossett set on a solo attempt to circumnavigate the globe in
August.
	   This voyage began Dec. 18, in Marrakech, Morocco, and covered
12,500 miles (20,000 kilometers). The goal was to eventually reach
Western Europe, after flying over southern Canada or Washington
state sometime Friday.
	   The craft was not immediately recovered, but Fossett said plans
were under way to salvage the capsule and its equipment.
	   During the journey, the team secured permission from 97
countries to cross their airspace. Iran, Iraq, Russia and North
Korea refused permission. The crew also had some tense moments when
they passed over China farther north than the balloon had been
authorized to fly.
	   A joint Australian-U.S. team plans to launch another attempt
next week. American real estate magnate Dave Liniger and his Remax
team are making final preparations in the Australian town of Alice
Springs to launch their giant balloon on or soon after Dec. 29.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Balloon Quest, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
