<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Khmer Rouge, 5th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Top Khmer Rouge leaders defect to government; Ta Mok still at large
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS analyst saying no trial threatens prime minister's
credibility, 11th-12th grafs
 &UR; By KER MUNTHIT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Two top Khmer Rouge leaders
considered architects of the group's genocidal reign of terror in
the 1970s defected to the government today. Khieu Samphan and Nuon
Chea said they wished to become ``ordinary citizens.''
	   Prime Minister Hun Sen said he personally negotiated what
amounts to the pair's surrender, and brushed aside questions of
whether they would be brought to trial for crimes against humanity.
	   ``We should not talk about any court,'' Hun Sen said. ``This is
a time when we should talk about reconciliation.''
	   Hun Sen's language indicated that a deal had been struck letting
Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea make peace with the government in
exchange for avoiding trial, despite pressure from the United
States and other countries to bring them to justice.
	   The deal involving Khieu Samphan, the nominal Khmer Rouge
leader, and Nuon Chea, the rebel movement's political chief,
appeared to finish off one of history's most brutal revolutionary
groups. It leaves at large only one major Khmer Rouge figure, the
one-legged general Ta Mok, and less than 100 loyalists.
	   Hun Sen, in a letter to King Norodom Sihanouk read over national
radio, said he ``would like to warmly welcome the two
personalities, and I hope this decision ... will become a
mobilization of strength for national reconstruction and peace.''
	   The two leaders were key figures in the Khmer Rouge's brutal
1975-79 rule, under which as many as 2 million people were killed.
	   The Khmer Rouge have waged a guerrilla war since their regime
was toppled by invading Vietnamese troops in 1979.
	   The Cambodian government and the United States have said they
wanted the two captured and tried for genocide and crimes against
humanity. It was unclear whether the defections meant the Cambodian
government would not pursue charges against them.
	   An aide to Hun Sen, Om Yentieng, said the prime minister
supports a tribunal for ex-leaders involved in genocide but that
justice should be left to local courts _ which are woefully
unequipped for such a task.
	   But an analyst said Hun Sen risks losing support from Cambodians
if he prevents a trial for at least one of the defectors.
	   ``With Nuon Chea, it is very clear he was involved in dealing
with security, prisoners and torture,'' said Youk Chhang, director
of a Cambodian research center devoted to gathering evidence
against the Khmer Rouge.
	   Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea, who were in the former rebel town
of Pailin in northwestern Cambodia, sent letters to Hun Sen
announcing they had broken from Ta Mok.
	   ``I have no other request except a request to be allowed to live
as a simple citizen,'' Khieu Samphan wrote in a copy of the letter
obtained by The Associated Press.
	   Nuon Chea wrote: ``I am honored to submit my request to the
Royal Government to return to society as an ordinary citizen to
take part in the consolidation of peace and stability.''
	   The U.S. Embassy did not immediately take calls from reporters
seeking comment.
	   The defections come just weeks after Khmer Rouge chief of staff
Khem Ngun and seven other generals surrendered and returned to the
Cambodian capital, Phnom Penh, for the first time in 19 years. That
surrender dealt a death blow to the guerrilla group.
	   Khem Ngun told The Associated Press that Khieu Samphan and Nuon
Chea had not attached any conditions to the surrender.
	   Khieu Samphan was the best-known Khmer Rouge intellectual, and
his polished manners led to his becoming the group's public face.
He was the official leader of the group for years, although real
power remained with Ta Mok and the infamous Pol Pot, who died of a
heart attack in April months after he was purged.
	   Nuon Chea was known as Brother Number Two, after Pol Pot. In May
1975, a month after the Khmer Rouge seized power, Nuon Chea laid
out the group's policy hallmarks _ destroying every vestige of a
market economy and killing suspected traitors.
	   In Thailand, which closely monitors Khmer Rouge activities, Maj.
Gen. Wiwat Sattarak, chief of the border task force, said that Ta
Mok has no more than 100 loyalist troops left.
	   ``The Cambodian government's attitude is to let him grow old and
die by himself,'' Wiwat said. ``It's not worth the money to chase
him.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Cambodia-Khmer Rouge, 5th Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
