<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Violence </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bloodshed continues in South Africa's KwaZuluX-Natal province
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DURBAN, South Africa (AP) _ Assailants shot to death two boys
and a young man in a region in eastern South Africa that has been
plagued by violence, police said Saturday.
	   One 21-year-old man survived the Christmas Day attack that
killed another 21-year-old and two 13-year-old boys, said police
spokesman Bala Naidoo.
	   No suspects have been caught and police did not know the motive
behind the attack, which occurred at 8:15 p.m. Friday in a house in
Umlazi, 20 kilometers (12 miles) south of the coastal city of
Durban.
	   Police were discounting any link with an attack on a Christmas
Eve party that killed eight people in the town of Margate. Those
killings happened after the gunmen apaprently tried to crash the
party but were refused entry.
	   ``It's totally unrelated to the Christmas Eve killings, which
happened 250 kilometers (155 miles) away,'' Naidoo said.
	   Both attacks happened in KwaZulu-Natal province, which in revent
years has been hit by violence, much of it politically inspired.
	   Fighting between followers of the Zulu-Nationalist Inkatha
Freedom Party and of the African National Congress in the years
before all-race elections in 1994 killed more than 10,000 people.
	   (aos)
</TEXT>
