<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yemen-Draft </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yemenis can avoid military service by paying dlrs 20 fee
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SAN`A, Yemen (AP) _ Yemenis can now avoid the country's
compulsory two-year military service by paying a fee equal to dlrs
20.
	   Yemeni President Ali Abdullah Saleh on Friday approved a bill
allowing men who do not wish to be drafted to pay 15 percent of a
conscript's monthly salary of 700 riyals (dlrs 5.6) for the two
years, the official Al-Thawra newspaper reported Saturday.
	   That amounts to a total of 2,520 riyals, or dlrs 20.
	   Economic analysts said the reason for the new law was to reduce
government expenses in line with economic reforms required by the
International Monetary Fund.
	   The government provides housing and clothing and pays a
transportation allowance as well as a monthly stipend to its
conscripts. No figures were available on the total amount of money
spent on conscripts.
	   Military service is compulsory in Yemen for men over 18.
	   Yemen has a foreign debt of some dlrs 10 billion. Most of its 17
million people live in poverty.
 &UR; str-fsa-ggl
</TEXT>
