<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-SAfrica-WIndies </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
West Indies fighting to stay in cricket match with South Africa
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos DUR101-103 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   DURBAN, South Africa (AP) _ South Africa kept the West Indies on
the back foot with three wickets in the second hour of play to have
the visitors at 69 for three at lunch on the first day of the third
test at Kingsmead Saturday.
	   With the West Indies using their ninth opening pair in 23 test
matches in Philo Wallace and retreaded wicketkeeper Junior Murray,
South African captain Hansie Cronje won the toss and sent the
tourists in to bat on a well-grassed pitch.
	   The West Indies are in a must-win situation, being two down in
the five-match series, and have made five changes to the team which
was beaten inside three days in the last match in Port Elizabeth.
In addition to Murray and Wallace, who returns after illness,
19-year-old Darren Ganga makes his debut, leg spinner Rawl Lewis
returns, and Franklyn Rose is included in place of Nixon McLean.
	   After putting on 50, the opening pair fell in quick succession,
Wallace falling to a poor shot to Jacques Kallis for 21, and Murray
being trapped in front by David Terbrugge just two runs later for
29. It seemed as if all the good work was to be undone when the
form man, Shivnarine Chanderpaul, succumbed to the wiles of Kallis
and an uncharacteristically injudicious shot for four.
	   At lunch, captain Brian Lara was not out on 10, and Carl Hooper
on two. There were glimmerings of some Lara form early on, after he
survived a snorter of an opening delivery from Terbrugge which
could have had him trapped in front had it not been called a
no-ball. He flicked Allan Donald off his hip for a lovely legside
boundary, and then stroked him through the covers gloriously just
before lunch.
	   (str)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
