<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Kidnapped Pigeons </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taiwanese gangs kidnap prize racing pigeons
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ Police said Saturday they arrested a
leading member of a gang that kidnapped prize racing pigeons and
collected ransoms totaling more than 50 million Taiwan dollars
(U.S. dlrs 1.5 million) from the owners.
	   Shen Pao-tien was arrested Saturday in Ilan, eastern Taiwan, but
six other members of his gang were still at large, police said.
	   The gang had kidnapped about 2,000 pigeons over the past two
years, said police, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
	   The birds were captured with nets during Taiwan's popular pigeon
races and their owners identified through the numbered rings the
birds wear around their ankles, police said.
	   Ransom demands topped 1 million Taiwan dollars (U.S. dlrs 3,000)
for some of the birds, they said.
	   Some owners were reluctant to contact police because the
kidnappers have been known to cut off the foot of a bird and mail
it to the owner.
	   The United Evening News said some gangsters bribed race
employees to tip them off about the times and routes of the races.
In many races, less than half of the racing pigeons safely reached
the final destination.
	   Despite cheating and kidnapping, the races remain popular with
gamblers because prizes can reach 100 million Taiwan dollars (U.S.
dlrs 300,000), the report said.
</TEXT>
