<SLUG> BC-Sports-Pakistan-Australia-Cricket,0186 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pakistan to record Australian cricketers' statements
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LAHORE, Pakistan (AP) _ A Pakistani judicial inquiry is sending
two people to Australia this week to record the statements of
disgraced Australian cricketers Mark Waugh and Shane Warne, cricket
authorities said Saturday.
	   The Pakistani inquiry is investigating allegations made by
Waugh, Warne and teammate Tim May that top Pakistani cricketers
were involved in match fixing.
	   However the inquiry says the testimony given by Waugh is suspect
following admissions by both Waugh and Warne that they took money
from an Indian bookmaker in exchange for information about pitch
and weather during a 1994 series.
	   The information affects the odds bookmakers give to people
betting on the game.
	   Pakistani cricket officials say Waugh made a false statement
when he appeared before the Pakistani judicial inquiry in October.
The inquiry is probing allegations that Pakistani cricketers Salim
Malik and Wasim Akram were involved in match fixing. The Pakistani
cricketers have denied the allegations.
</TEXT>
