<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-Nuclear,0312 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pakistan rejects unilateral moratorium on fissile material
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) _ Pakistan, one of the world's newest
nuclear powers, rejected a unilateral moratorium on fissile
material used to make nuclear bombs Saturday.
	   ``Given our genuine security concerns, we cannot agree to any
demand for a moratorium on the production of fissile materials
unilaterally or multilaterally,'' Foreign Minister Sartaj Aziz told
the National Assembly or powerful lawmaking Lower House of
Parliament.
	   Both Pakistan and India exploded underground nuclear tests last
May, declared themselves nuclear powers and generated global fears
of a nuclear arms race on the Asian subcontinent, a volatile region
that already has seen three wars in the last 51 years.
	   Aziz says the United States and other western countries have
asked Pakistan to declare an early moratorium on the production of
fissile material.
	   But Aziz says Pakistan has concerns about India's stockpile of
fissile material, as well as stockpiles worldwide.
	   ``We believe that a fissile material treaty should be an
instrument promoting both nuclear non-proliferation and nuclear
disarmament,'' Aziz said. ``When the substantive negotiations start
on Fissile Material Cut-off Treaty in Geneva next year, Pakistan
will pursue its position, which is shared by a majority of the
non-aligned countries.''
	   Both India and Pakistan are under fierce pressure from the
international community to sign the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty,
something Pakistan already has expressed a willingness to do.
International sanctions imposed following the underground tests
were relaxed after Pakistan indicated it would sign the test ban
treaty.
	   However, the Pakistan government has been steadfast in its
refusal to sign the pact ending the production of fissile material.
</TEXT>
