<HEADLINE>
After Christmas engagements, pope relaxes at holiday retreat
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CASTEL GANDOLFO, Italy (AP) _ After a bout with the flu and the
demands of Christmas appearances, Pope John Paul II on Saturday
bantered with pilgrims as he began a brief holiday in the Alban
hills southeast of Rome.
	   Following celebration of a Christmas Eve midnight Mass, which
lasted into the early hours of Friday, and then another appearance
to the public gathered in St. Peter's Square at noon on Christmas
day, John Paul scheduled a late morning helicopter flight Saturday
for Castel Gandolfo, a lakeside hilltown which hosts the papal
holiday retreat.
	   ``Merry Christmas, Castel Gandolfo,'' the pope joked after
giving his blessing to pilgrims and tourists in the courtyard of
the 17th-century palace.
	   John Paul, who is to spend a few days in the hilltown, seemed
rested and in good spirits in the crisp, sunny day. On Dec. 18, the
Vatican announced that the pope had canceled some private audiences
because of a light flu and fever.
	   (fd)
