<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Myanmar-Suu Kyi </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pro-democracy leader won't let government deport her
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   YANGON, Myanmar (AP) _ Nobel Peace Prize-winner Aung San Suu Kyi
has told members of her party that she won't allow Myanmar's
military regime to deport her.
	   The opposition National League for Democracy said in a statement
obtained Saturday that Suu Kyi told members last week not to worry
about rumors that she would be deported after the New Year.
	   ``Party members should not be worried of my deportation,'' Suu
Kyi said. ``I am not a citizen of other countries and I have no
intention of leaving this country.''
	   Suu Kyi is married to a British academic, Michael Aris. The
government often refers to her a spy and puppet of foreign nations,
particularly former colonial ruler Britain and the United States.
	   ``I am not a British citizen and my conscience is clear,'' said
Suu Kyi. ``How can a government deport its citizen if there is no
country to accept him or her?''
	   Suu Kyi, daughter of independence hero Aung San, has spent most
of the past decade under house arrest or had her movements
restricted in a struggle with the military rulers for more
democracy.
	   Though she was under house arrest at the time, her party won
parliamentary elections allowed by the military in 1990. The ruling
council of generals never allowed the parliament to meet.
	   The party launched a campaign earlier this year to convene the
parliament unilaterally, triggering a roundup of hundreds of
members. Only those promising to quit her party have been freed.
	   Recently, the ruling State Peace and Development Council has
been organizing mass rallies demanding Suu Kyi be deported, echoed
by commentaries in official newspapers.
</TEXT>
