<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Chechnya </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bodies of four kidnapped foreigners found in Chechnya
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The bodies of four foreigners beheaded in Chechnya
earlier this month were found on the outskirts of the Chechen
capital Grozny, a news report said Saturday.
	   The bodies of the four men _ Peter Kennedy, Darren Hickey and
Rudolf Petschi of Britain, and New Zealand's Stanley Shaw _ were
found late Friday night, said Chechen presidential spokesman
Mairbek Vachagayev, according to the ITAR-Tass news agency.
	   The foreigners' heads were found on a roadside Dec. 8, after a
rescue attempt by local authorities apparently went wrong. The men,
all engineers in Chechnya to install a cellular phone system, were
kidnapped in early October.
	   Officials said the bodies would be sent to Britain.
	   Authorities have accused a rebel warlord of killing the four
men, but have provided no evidence to support their claim. The
warlord, Arbi Barayev, denies the charges.
	   Chechnya has been plagued by violence and kidnappings,
especially since its 1994-96 independence war against Russia. It
runs its own affairs though no country recognizes its claims of
sovereignty.
	   (nw/ren)
</TEXT>
