<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0671 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of news from The Associated Press. Some items have
moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f'' category
codes:
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Two leaders of the Khmer Rouge reign
of terror in the 1970s defected to the government Saturday in a
deal that could signal the end of the bloodstained revolutionary
group but is unlikely to bring them to justice. Prime Minister Hun
Sen said he personally negotiated the final touches on the
defections Friday night, the 20th anniversary of the Christmas 1978
invasion by Vietnam that toppled the genocidal regime. Khieu
Samphan, the Khmer Rouge's nominal leader, and political chief Nuon
Chea said in letters read by Hun Sen on national radio that they
wished to become ``ordinary citizens.'' Hun Sen later brushed aside
questions whether they would be brought to trial for the deaths of
as many as 2 million Cambodians, indicating a deal had been struck
allowing them to surrender in exchange for not being tried. ``We
should not talk about any court,'' Hun Sen said. ``This is a time
when we should talk about reconciliation.'' (CAMBODIA-KHMER ROUGE)
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Solidifying his support among the
military, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic has appointed a new
air force chief and promoted loyalists who back his Kosovo
policies, media here reported Saturday. The moves followed last
month's sacking of the chief of Yugoslavia's army, who was
reportedly critical of Milosevic's handling of the Kosovo crisis
and his replacement with a neo-communist supporter of the Yugoslav
president. The appointments and promotions came amid a dangerous
escalation in clashes in Kosovo this week that threaten to return
the Albanian-majority province of Serbia, Yugoslavia's major
republic, to all-out war. (YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO)
	   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) _ A fishing boat with six people on
board was missing Saturday after Cyclone Cora battered the Pacific
island nation of Tonga, Tongan police said. The 7-meter (yard) boat
was missing in high seas off the central Ha'apai group of islands.
The cyclone, which had moved away from Tonga's main island
Tongatapu by 6 p.m. local time (0400 GMT), was reported to have
damaged crops and buildings and cut communications lines throughout
the island group. The cyclone battered the main island of Tongatapu
and the Ha'apai chain with wind gusts of up to 100 mph (160 kph), a
police spokesman said. (TONGA-CYCLONE)
	   HONOLULU (AP) _ After three failed attempts this year to float
around the world in a balloon, American millionaire Steve Fossett
sounded a little discouraged. ``I think it's time to go sailing,''
Fossett said Friday after he and two other adventurers abandoned
their effort to make the first nonstop around-the-world balloon
flight. British mogul Richard Branson, however, said he was
undeterred. ``We've finally cracked everything in the technology,''
he said. ``We'll buck up ourselves and start again.'' Fossett,
Branson, and Per Lindstrand of Sweden, who have made a total of 11
attempts at a nonstop flight around globe, were in good condition
when U.S. Coast Guard helicopters lifted them out of the Pacific
Ocean about 10 miles (16 kilometers) off Kahuku Point at the
northeast tip of Oahu. They were seven days into their journey _
about the halfway point _ when they ditched. (BALLOON QUEST)
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Police charged a businessman and his
girlfriend Saturday with trying to defect to communist North Korea
to avoid fraud charges at home. Businessman Kim Hak-hee, 48, and
his girlfriend Lee Soo-ok, 39, who fled South Korea in 1993, met
North Korean embassy officials in Singapore on Dec. 14 to arrange
their defection through Beijing, authorities said. Kim and Lee were
captured Tuesday by Interpol in the Kuala Lumpur airport while
stopping for a transit flight for Beijing, and where extradited to
South Korea, police said.
</TEXT>
