<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Politics </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkish president pushes parliament
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo ANK101 &QL; 
 &UR; By SELCAN HACAOGLU &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ Turkey's president on Saturday pushed the
heavily fragmented Turkish Parliament to try to reach a consensus
on a new government.
	   Demirel's remarks came two days before Yalim Erez, an
independent lawmaker who was designated as premier by the president
on Wednesday, starts negotiations with party leaders.
	   If Erez fails to form a coalition soon, Demirel could appoint a
caretaker government to run the country until elections on April
18.
	   But Demirel made clear he wanted a government in place soon with
a real coalition.
	   ``I am seeking a consensus,'' Demirel said.
	   ``I will not form a government which is not based on
Parliament's confidence,'' Demirel told reporters in a year-end
news conference. ``If Erez cannot form a government by Jan. 10,
then new searches begin for new government formulas.''
	   A vote of confidence is not required for a caretaker government.
	   Erez, who is expected to ask a range of parties to join his
Cabinet, must submit any eventual coalition to a parliamentary vote
of confidence to see if it can command a majority in the
legislature.
	   Demirel's refusal to appoint a caretaker government is another
setback for the pro-Islamic Virtue Party since under such an
arrangement the party would be granted 10 ministry posts to reflect
its standing as Parliament's largest party.
	   Demirel already snubbed Virtue by appointing Erez, the acting
industry and trade minister, breaking with the tradition of asking
the leader of the largest party to try to form a government.
	   Virtue is the successor of a banned Islamic party, Welfare, that
was pressured out of government by the military last year for
anti-secular activities.
	   The coalition government led by Mesut Yilmaz collapsed Nov. 25
over allegations that the acting premier rigged the sale of a bank.
	   Before Erez, veteran leftist politician Bulent Ecevit spent
three weeks in a failed bid to form a coalition with Turkey's
bickering center-left and center-right parties.
	   (sh-fd) 	   
</TEXT>
