w1899 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Burundi-Attacks     12-26 0242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Burundi-Attacks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Seven killed in rebel attacks in Burundi
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUJUMBURA, Burundi (AP) _ Rebel attackers have killed at least
seven people in southwestern Burundi, the official news agency ABP
reported.
	   In a dispatch Friday, ABP said four people were killed Wednesday
in Rumonge commune in Bururi province, and another five people were
kidnapped.
	   The agency said Hutu rebels trying to oust the government of
President Pierre Buyoya left pamphlets behind ``to intimidate
people.''
	   Another three people were killed Tuesday in an attack on Munege
village, ABP said.
	   During a conference in the Kenyan capital, Nairobi, earlier this
week to discuss prospects for peace in the tiny central African
nation, Burundian legislators expressed concern about possible
violence over the Christmas and New Year's holidays by FNL rebels,
the armed wing of the rebel Palipehutu group.
	   Last New Year's Eve, FNL attacks around Bujumbura airport left
more than 200 people dead.
	   Palipehutu has been opposed to the ongoing Burundian peace
process that has brought about a partial cessation of attacks by
another rebel group and agreement by parties representing minority
Tutsis and majority Hutus to work together.
	   At least 200,000 people have died in Burundi, most of them
civilians, since Tutsi paratroopers killed the country's first
democratically elected president, a Hutu, in an failed coup in
October 1993.
	   (ag/sl)	   
</TEXT>
