w1900 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Germany-WetRide     12-26 0161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Wet Ride </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Onboard computer navigator forgets to mention ferry
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   POTSDAM, Germany (AP) _ A German couple out for a Christmas
drive near Berlin ended up in a river _ apparently because their
onboard computer navigator forgot to mention they had to wait for a
ferry.
	   The 57-year-old driver and his passenger were not injured in the
accident, police said Saturday.
	   The couple was out driving Friday night when they came to
Caputh, where a ferry operates across the Havel River.
	   That information, however, apparently was never stored in the
satellite-steered navigation system they were using, police said.
The driver kept going straight in the dark, expecting a bridge, and
ended up in the water.
	   Ship traffic on the river was stopped for two hours while the
luxury car was fished out about 4 meters (13 feet) from the river
bank.
	   ``You can't always blindly rely on technology,'' a coast guard
police officer said.
