w1902 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Israel-Palestinians     12-26 0305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinians </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Palestinians demand Israeli compliance with peace pact
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NASSER SHIYOUKHI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HEBRON, West Bank (AP) _ Palestinians are demanding that Israel
lift its suspension of the Wye River peace accord, saying the
ongoing election campaign is no reason to freeze the process.
	   ``This Israeli government continues to be a government,
responsible for its commitments,'' chief Palestinian negotiator
Saeb Erekat said after Friday night's meeting of the Palestinian
Cabinet in the West Bank town of Hebron.
	   Israel has said its election timetable _ direct balloting for
prime minister is expected by late April _ is not affecting the
peace process.
	   However, the call for early elections was triggered by
lawmakers' rejection of Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's peace
policies, and how and whether to implement the peace pact is
already a major campaign issue.
	   Israel says it froze the 2-month-old U.S.-brokered accord
because of Palestinian violations, and has refused to go ahead with
promised troop pullbacks from the West Bank unless the Palestinians
meet a series of conditions. Those include a renunciation of
Palestinian claims to the right to declare statehood in May 1999
whether or not terms have been agreed on with Israel.
	   But the Palestinian Cabinet said in a statement following its
meeting that it would continue making preparations for a statehood
declaration in May.
	   The Palestinians also said they would seek help from the Arab
world and the rest of the international community to ``confront the
freezing of the peace process.
	   The Cabinet called Israeli noncompliance with the accord a
``dangerous development which was initiated by the Israeli
government without any reason besides its rejection of peace.''
 &UR; (str-lk)
</TEXT>
