w1915 &Cx1f; wstm-
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Cricket-SAfric 1stLd-Writethru   12-26 0459
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-SAfrica-WIndies, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
West Indies fighting to stay in cricket match with South Africa
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with play up to tea &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos DUR101-103

<TEXT>
	   DURBAN, South Africa (AP) _ South Africa's backup pace bowlers
kept the West Indies in enough trouble at 156 for five wickets at
tea on the first day of the third test at Kingsmead Saturday.
	   Captain Brian Lara scored only the West Indies second half
century in tests on the tour as he made 51 attractive runs before
falling to his second mistimed pull shot in as many innings for 51
to David Terbrugge. Lara was understandably furious with himself,
with his dismissal being the fourth to a bad stroke in the innings.
	   South Africa's star strike bowler, Allan Donald, and Lara had
had a fascinating duel earlier in the visitor's innings, with Lara
coming off the better of the two. While that battle raged, it
looked as if Lara was approaching his best, but, at tea, the West
Indies were left with two inexperienced players at the crease in
Darren Ganga, not out on 24, and wicketkeeper Ridley Jacobs on 14.
	   Earlier, Carl Hooper had gone for 10 to an atrocious flash
outside the off stump off the bowling of Jacques Kallis, easily the
best of the South African bowlers with three for 18.
	   With the West Indies using their ninth opening pair in 23 test
matches in Philo Wallace and retreaded wicketkeeper Junior Murray,
South African captain Hansie Cronje won the toss and sent the
tourists in to bat on a well-grassed pitch that looks likely to
take turn as the match progresses.
	   The West Indies are in a must-win situation, being two down in
the five-match series, and have made five changes to the team which
was beaten inside three days in the last match in Port Elizabeth.
In addition to Murray and Wallace, who returns after illness,
19-year-old Ganga makes his debut, leg spinner Rawl Lewis returns,
and Franklyn Rose is included in place of Nixon McLean.
	   After putting on 50, the opening pair fell in quick succession,
Wallace falling to a poor shot to Kallis for 21, and Murray being
trapped in front by Terbrugge just two runs later for 29. It seemed
as if all the good work was to be undone when the form man,
Shivnarine Chanderpaul, succumbed to the wiles of Kallis and an
uncharacteristically injudicious shot for four.
	   At lunch, Lara was not out on 10, and Hooper on two. There were
glimmerings of some Lara form early on, after he survived a snorter
of an opening delivery from Terbrugge which could have had him
trapped in front had it not been called a no-ball. He flicked
Donald off his hip for a lovely legside boundary, and then stroked
him through the covers gloriously just before lunch.
	   (str)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Cricket-SAfrica-WIndies, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:s; 
