w1920 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MiddleEastBusinessBri     12-26 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Middle East Business Briefs </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Jordan, Kuwait and Iran.

<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Jordan's economic growth rate for the year
1998 is expected to amount to 2.2 percent, an official of the
International Monetary Fund was quoted Saturday as saying.
	   Antonio Fertido, director of the IMF Middle East department,
made the comment in an interview with the Jordanian daily Al-Ra'i.
	   He also said an IMF delegation will visit the kingdom next month
to study the economy and discuss ways of speeding up growth.
	   The IMF estimate is in line with projections from Jordan's
planning minister, Nabil Amari.
	   The economy grew 1.8 percent last year after it was set back by
the U.N. trade embargo on Iraq and the barriers put by Israel on
Jordanian products destined for the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
 &UR; ___
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ The government has pumped around 1 billion dinars
(dlrs 3.31 billion) it made from a privatization program into
state-owned institutions and companies, a senior official said in
remarks published Saturday.
	   Ali al-Bader, who heads the Kuwait Investment Authority, told
the Kuwaiti daily Al-Rai Al-Amm that some of the money was also
used to bridge Kuwait's budget deficits. The investment authority
is the government arm that manages the country's state investments,
which are worth an estimated dlrs 40 billion, mostly abroad.
	   The official said the funds were used to increase the capital of
the state-owned Credits and Loans Bank, the Housing Authority and
other government firms. He did not provide details.
	   The government has for four years been selling its stake in
scores of local companies, part of a plan to boost the private
sector and energize the economy which is dominated by oil revenues
and government spending.
	   The value of holdings it still intends to sell off is around 800
million dinars (dlrs 2.64 billion).
	   Kuwait has for years been reaching into its foreign investments
to bridge budget shortfalls. The small Gulf state, which has been
hard hit by falling oil prices, expects a net deficit of more than
1.92 billion dinars (dlrs 6.35 billion) in the fiscal year that
started July 1.
 &UR; ___
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ An Iranian expert says he expects no rise in
future oil prices and urged Iran to revamp is taxation system and
diversify its industries to reduce the budget deficit, the official
Islamic Republic News Agency said Saturday.
	   The agency said Mohammad Qoli Yusefi, a university lecturer,
told the English-language Tehran Times that one reason he expected
no great rise in oil prizes is that the industrialized nations have
turned into service economies.
	   He also said that he expected no increase in demand for oil
because energy-saving devices were reducing the need for oil and
that natural gas was proving to be a good alternative.
	   Yusefi pointed out that reliance on oil revenues as the main
source of income by oil-producing states has resulted in an ailing
taxation system. He said Iran should deregulate industry and
facilitate export of non-oil goods.
 &UR; var-ggl
</TEXT>
