<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Student Prayer </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian students pray for activists killed in street clashes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ About 100 people, many of them
students, held a Muslim prayer session Saturday to commemorate the
deaths of student protesters in clashes last month with security
forces.
	   It was the first gathering of political activists since the
beginning a week ago of the Islamic holy month of Ramadan, during
which anti-government protesters have pledged to refrain from
street rallies. Indonesia is predominately Muslim.
	   The night prayer was held in the parking lot of Atma Jaya
Catholic University, the scene of fighting between anti-riot
officers and students who were trying to march to Parliament.
	   The Nov. 13 clashes left nine students dead and triggered
rioting in several parts of Jakarta, the Indonesian capital, on the
following day.
	   ``We hope that the dead students are accepted by God and we
gather here in the hopes of avoiding more victims in the future,''
a student said in a speech at the university, which is beside
Jakarta's main thoroughfare.
	   Other students knelt on prayer mats and intoned, ``God is
great.''
	   Last month, students had been protesting against a government
assembly on political reforms, which they rejected because many of
its members were appointed by former President Suharto. The
authoritarian leader was ousted in May after 32 years in power.
	   His successor, President B.J. Habibie, has implemented some
reforms and has scheduled parliamentary elections in June. But he
has not yielded to student demands to put Suharto on trial and
strip the military of its powerful political role.
</TEXT>
