</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Nuclear </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nuclear reactor stopped in Ukraine
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ A nuclear reactor was stopped for
unscheduled repairs at Ukraine's Yuzhnaya power plant, forcing a
delay in repairs that had been planned at another nuclear facility,
officials said Saturday.
	   The repairs at Yuzhnaya's reactor No. 3 were prompted by growing
hydrogen leaks from its cooling system and are expected to be
finished by Monday, the Nuclear Regulation Administration said.
	   The reactor shutdown led to an electricity shortage in Ukraine's
energy system and forced energy officials to postpone repairs at
the Zaporizhia nuclear power plant, where one reactor was to have
been stopped Saturday for a week.
	   Ukraine's power plants, which are owed more than dlrs 1 billion
by electricity consumers, have been working below capacity since
October because they don't have enough money for fuel. As a result,
they cannot meet increased winter energy demands. Many villages and
enterprises throughout Ukraine suffer hours-long power cuts every
day.
	   Energy shortages forced the Energy Ministry to delay lengthy
repairs on the only operational reactor at the Chernobyl power
plant earlier this month, despite growing international concerns
over its safety.
	   Ukraine's five nuclear power plants provide more than 40 percent
of the former Soviet republic's energy needs. Four of the country's
14 operational reactors are currently undergoing repair.
	   (vl/nw/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
