w1931 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 1stLd-Writethru   12-26 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru,0614 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede PRISTINA
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Milosevic continues army reshuffle, appoints new air force chief
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with new appointments in military, Serb farmer killed;
trims. Changes byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By KATARINA KRATOVAC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Solidifying his support among the
military, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic has appointed a new
air force chief and promoted loyalists who back his Kosovo
policies, media here reported Saturday.
	   The moves followed last month's sacking of the chief of
Yugoslavia's army, who was reportedly critical of Milosevic's
handling of the Kosovo crisis and his replacement with a
neo-communist supporter of the Yugoslav president.
	   The appointments and promotions came amid a dangerous escalation
in clashes in Kosovo this week that threaten to return the
Albanian-majority province of Serbia, Yugoslavia's major republic,
to all-out war.
	   The promotions were announced after a session late Friday of the
Supreme Defense Council, the country's five-member decision-making
body for top defense issues, headed by Milosevic.
	   The daily Politika carried a front-page announcement that
Lt.-Gen. Spasoje Smiljanic was appointed commander of the air
force, a position that had been vacated in October when the former
air force chief was deposed.
	   Milosevic also promoted seven generals, including three who were
involved in the Yugoslav army campaign against Kosovo's separatist
Albanian guerillas this year.
	   A commander of the army corps in provincial capital Pristina was
moved up to head a regional section of the Yugoslav army, while a
former chief of special forces in Kosovo was made his aide.
	   Another loyalist was appointed new commander in the region of
Pristina.
	   Milosevic also relieved three high-ranking army officers of
their duties but it was not immediately clear whether they were
purged for suspected disloyalty.
	   Last month's deposition of the former army chief, Gen. Momcilo
Perisic, was a result of his opposition both to the neo-communist
party run by Milosevic's wife, Mirjana Markovic, and of Milosevic's
hard-line stand on Kosovo.
	   There had also been growing rumors in Belgrade that the ruling
couple feared a coup attempt by Perisic and the secret police
chief, the second most powerful man in Yugoslavia, whom Milosevic
dismissed earlier in November.
	   In Kosovo on Saturday, the government-run Media Center said that
the Kosovo Liberation Army killed an elderly Serb farmer _ one of
the few Serbs who had not left the area, near the town of Podujevo.
	   Serb and Yugoslav forces launched an offensive in the region on
Thursday, reportedly killing at least nine people. The crackdown
poses the gravest threat yet to the Oct. 12 agreement that halted
months of violence between Serbs and guerrillas trying to gain
Kosovo's independence.
	   William Walker, head of an international force monitoring the
Kosovo situation, said the newest fighting _ just south of Podujevo
_ had led to the ``tensest period since the agreement was signed.''
	   The United States, France and the European Union have warned
both sides not to continue the violence. Russian Foreign Minister
Igor Ivanov on Friday warned the West against using force to halt
the latest violence.
	   In October, NATO threatened airstrikes against the Serbs as
punishment for their crackdown begun last February, in which
hundreds died and some 300,000 were forced to flee their homes. The
NATO attacks were put on hold after a cease-fire was reached and
Milosevic pulled out some of his forces.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:ASIA;)
(REG:AFRI;)
