<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Illegal Immigrants </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Calm seas off Italy draws illegal immigrants to shore
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Encouraged by calm seas, more than 200 illegal
immigrants from Kosovo, Iraq and other places sailed to Italy's
southeastern coast over a 24-hour period, Italian news reports said
Saturday.
	   A group of 150 clandestine immigrants, more than half of them
children, arrived Friday night in two big rubber dinghies, and were
taken to detention centers, where they will stay until authorities
decide if they must be sent back home.
	   In the early hours of Saturday, more than 50 people, most of
them from Kosovo, turned up in the Gargano area, the ``spur'' of
the Italian boot-shaped peninsula. The arrivals included a pregant
woman from Kosovo and a Filipino family of seven.
	   Most immigrant hopefuls see Italy as a gateway to relatives and
jobs in northern Europe. They pay smugglers money to bring them
from Asia, eastern Europe and Africa to take them to Italian
shores, but organizers commonly abandon their charges in the seas
off Italy to avoid being caught by navy and coast guard patrols.
	   (fd)
</TEXT>
