<HEADER>
w1945 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Spain-BasqueGovernmen     12-26 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Spain-Basque Government </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New Basque government to rely on party linked to ETA separatists
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CIARAN GILES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ Two nationalist Basque parties signed a
pact Saturday to form a minority regional government whose survival
looks certain to depend on support from a group linked to the armed
separatist organization ETA.
	   Two months after elections were staged, Xabier Arzalluz of the
region's leading Basque Nationalist Party signed a four-year deal
with Carlos Garaikoetxea from the Euskal Alkartasuna party.
	   Arzalluz's party won 21 seats in the 75-seat regional parliament
while Euskal Alkartasuna garnered six.
	   The two have acknowledged they will be banking on outside
support from Euskal Herritarrok, a political group which won 14
seats, and which is dominated by Herri Batasuna, long recognized as
the political wing of ETA.
	   It will be the first time a Basque government has been pacted
entirely by pro-independence parties since the Basque region was
given autonomous powers in 1979 following the death of dictator
Francisco Franco.
	   The accord comes as Spain enjoys its fourth month of peace as
ETA continues to uphold its unilateral cease-fire begun Sept. 18.
The cease-fire followed months of talks between the Basque
Nationalist Party and Herri Batasuna.
	   ETA has killed nearly 800 people since 1968 in its campaign for
independence.
	   Euskal Herritarrok has said it will not form part of a new
government, but would lend support on certain votes. The deal's
first test comes Tuesday when the parliament meets to vote in a new
regional president with the Basque Nationalist Party's Juan Jose
Ibarretxe tipped to win.
	   The new coalition excludes Spain's two main parties _ Prime
Minister Jose Maria Aznar's ruling center-right Popular Party and
the opposition Socialists, both of whom are steadfast in their
opposition to a split in Spanish unity.
	   The Popular Party placed second in the Basque elections with 16
seats, while the Socialists took 14. Both parties have strongly
criticized the Basque Nationalist Party's dealings with Herri
Batasuna and insist Herri Batasuna and ETA must renounce the armed
campaign.
	   Six Popular Party members have been killed by ETA over the last
three years.
	   The nationalists argue that bringing Euskal Herritarrok and
Herri Batasuna into the fold will help with cement the peace
process.
	   Prime Minister Aznar has said he is open to talks to permanently
resolve the Basque conflict but demands that ETA should give
greater proof that it intends ending the violence.
	   (cg)
</TEXT>
