<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Middle East Business Briefs, 1st Add </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ Low oil prices will deepen Kuwait's projected net
deficit by about 200 million dinars (dlrs 662.25 million), the
finance minister told parliament Saturday.
	   The shortfall for fiscal 1998-99, which started July 1, is
estimated to be about 1.92 billion dinars (dlrs 6.35 billion).
	   It was based on oil revenues of dlrs 10 a barrel, but ``we have
to make our calculations at dlrs 8 a barrel if we are to be
realistic,'' the minister, Sheik Ali Salem al-Ali al-Sabah, told
the legislature.
	   The house was discussing economic reform and the effect of
sagging oil prices. Sales of crude oil are the backbone of the
economy of this small Gulf state.
	   The deputy prime minister and foreign minister, Sheik Sabah
al-Ahmed al-Sabah, warned ``the situation was serious and needed to
be remedied as soon as possible.''
	   He called on his countrymen to accept the growing need for
charging for some public services and cutting state subsidies on
others. Most lawmakers oppose such unpopular steps and demand the
government should first clamp down on wasteful spending and the
theft of public money.
 &UR; de-jbm
