<HEADLINE>
Japanese doomsday cult trying to regroup, report says
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The Japanese doomsday cult accused of a 1995 gas
attack on Tokyo subways is trying to regroup and recruit new
members, a news report said Saturday.
	   The Aum Shinri Kyo religious cult is one of several groups
monitored by Japan's Public Security Investigation Agency in a
report released Saturday, Kyodo News service said.
	   ``Aum is actively attempting to bring back former members and
recruiting new members on a nationwide basis, while initiating
advertising campaigns and acquiring necessary capital,'' Kyodo
quoted the report as saying.
	   The agency's report also discussed Japanese right-wing and
international terrorist groups, Kyodo said.
	   A top Aum member was sentenced to death in October for the
murder of a lawyer and his family. Other members including guru
Shoko Asahara are on trial for the subway attack, which killed a
dozen.
