<SLUG> BC-Italy-Obit-Cherchi </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Italian sculptor, part of '30s movement, dies in Turin
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TURIN, Italy (AP) _ Sandro Cherchi, a sculptor who was a founder
of an anti-fascist artistic movement in Italy in the 1930s, has
died in his home in Turin, Italian RAI state TV reported Saturday.
	   No cause of death was given for Cherchi, who was 87.
	   Born in Genoa in 1911, he moved to Milan in 1936, where, two
years later, he helped found, along with painter Renato Guttoso,
sculptor Giacomo Manzu, writer Ernesto Treccani and others, the
dynamic artistic and literary movement known as ``Corrente''
(Italian for current as well as for electricity).
	   Cherchi's scuptures included work in plastic. They were
exhibited at the Venice Biennale art exhibit in years 1948 through
1956. Among those holding works permanently of the artist is
Florence's Uffizi museum.
	   While considered to be in the abstract genre, his works
reflected a streak of realism as well.
	   Details on funeral arrangements and any survivors were not
immediately available.
	   (fd) 	   
</TEXT>
