u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Cricket-SAfric 2ndLd-Writethru   12-26 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-SAfrica-WIndies, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
West Indies batsmen fail again in cricket match with South Africa
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with end of day's play
 &UR; AP Photos DUR101-103

<TEXT>
	   DURBAN, South Africa (AP) _ The West Indies batsmen failed to
grasp the initiative as South Africa dismissed them for 198 on the
first day of the third test at Kingsmead Saturday. At the close of
play, South Africa was on 46 without loss.
	   After glimpses of what might have been for the tourists if their
batsmen had knuckled down and played no-risk cricket, they ended up
losing their last five wickets for 42 runs in a poor display in the
hour after tea. Until then, South Africa's backup pace bowlers had
kept the West Indies in check, with Jacques Kallis and David
Terbrugge taking five between them as strike bowlers Allan Donald
and Shaun Pollock seemed unable to make the breakthrough although
Pollock was perhaps unlucky.
	   And then, towards the end of the innings it was the unlikely
bowling of captain Hansie Cronje which wrapped up the tail as he
took three wickets for 19 in his 4.1 overs. Ridley Jacobs (39) Rawl
Lewis (0) and Franklyn Rose (6) were his victims, and Curtly
Ambrose was run out by a direct hit from Jonty Rhodes.
	   South Africa saw out the final 16 overs of the day with Gary
Kirsten not out on 15, and Hershelle Gibbs on 26. With their
opening pair averaging just 15.1 in the last 19 test innings, and
passing 25 just once, this little cameo by Gibbs and Kirsten could
be very valuable for South Africa.
	   There was not too much to worry the South African batsmen,
although their entire stint at the crease was under floodlights.
Both teams agreed to this playing condition, something which has
been tried in South African domestic cricket with a degree of
success.
	   Captain Brian Lara scored only the West Indies second half
century in tests on the tour as he made 51 attractive runs before
falling to his second mistimed pull shot in as many innings for 51
to Terbrugge. Lara was understandably furious with himself, with
his dismissal being the fourth to a bad stroke in the innings.
	   South Africa's star strike bowler, Donald, and Lara had had a
fascinating duel earlier in the visitors' innings, with Lara coming
off the better of the two. While that battle raged, it looked as if
Lara was approaching his ominous best, but, at tea, the West Indies
were left with two inexperienced players at the crease in Darren
Ganga, not out on 24, and wicketkeeper Jacobs on 14.
	   Earlier, Carl Hooper had gone for 10 to an atrocious flash
outside the off stump off the bowling of Kallis easily the best of
the South African bowlers with three for 18.
	   With the West Indies using their ninth opening pair in 23 test
matches in Philo Wallace and retreaded wicketkeeper Junior Murray,
South African captain Cronje won the toss and sent the tourists in
to bat on a well-grassed pitch that looks likely to take turn as
the match progresses.
	   The West Indies are in a must-win situation, being two down in
the five-match series, and have made five changes to the team which
was beaten inside three days in the last match in Port Elizabeth.
In addition to Murray and Wallace, who returns after illness,
19-year-old Ganga makes his debut, leg spinner Lewis returns, and
Franklyn Rose is included in place of Nixon McLean.
	   After putting on 50, the opening pair fell in quick succession,
Wallace falling to a poor shot to Kallis for 21, and Murray being
trapped in front by Terbrugge just two runs later for 29. It seemed
as if all the good work was to be undone when the form man,
Shivnarine Chanderpaul, succumbed to the wiles of Kallis and an
uncharacteristically injudicious shot for four.
	   At lunch, Lara was not out on 10, and Hooper on two. There were
glimmerings of some Lara form early on, after he survived a snorter
of an opening delivery from Terbrugge which could have had him
trapped in front had it not been called a no-ball. He flicked
Donald off his hip for a lovely legside boundary, and then stroked
him through the covers gloriously just before lunch.
	   Play resumes at 10 a.m. (0800 GMT) Sunday.
	   (str)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Cricket-SAfrica-WIndies, 2nd Ld-Writethru; CT:s; 
