w2048 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SierraLeone     12-26 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sierra Leone </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rebels claim 60 killed; Freetown prepares for attack
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CLARENCE ROY-MACAULAY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) _ Fearing an impending rebel assault
on Sierra Leone's capital, angry residents surged through the
streets Saturday and sought out mob justice against least two men
accused of being rebel spies.
	   The rebel Revolutionary United Front, meanwhile, reported they
had killed 60 Nigerian soldiers belonging to the West African
intervention force known as ECOMOG while capturing the town of
Makeni. On Saturday the rebels dragged the bodies through the
streets with an armored car ``as an example to everyone,'' rebel
Gen. Sam Bockarie said. His claims could not be independently
confirmed.
	   The government bolstered Freetown's defenses by trucking in
traditional militiamen known as Kamajors from rural villages and
flying in soldiers from Nigeria and Ghana to reinforce ECOMOG
troops.
	   Chanting marchers thronged through a downtown square in the
capital where government officials addressed them calling for calm,
before the mob singled out two young men accused of being rebels in
civilian disguise.
	   The victims were severely beaten before the crowd thrust
gasoline-filled tires around their necks and set them alight. Their
charred remains were carried away by police, who did not attempt to
stop the killings.
	   Several other mob attacks were reported around Freetown but
could not be confirmed.
	   The Kamajor militiamen, members of a secret society of hunters
and traditional fighters, wore leather tunics and carried rusty
guns and machetes in the bustling city streets, setting up
checkpoints and carrying out random searches of pedestrians and
drivers.
	   Together with ECOMOG, the militia has been given defense duties
by Sierra Leone's government which dissolved the country's
rebellious military earlier this year.
	   Remnants of that military and their rebel allies who took power
for a 10 month period following a bloody May 1997 coup have over
the past week launched lightning attacks against loyalist forces
throughout the country.
	   Refugees fleeing the fighting have flooded into Freetown and
rebels have threatened to attack the capital unless the government
releases their imprisoned leader, Foday Sankoh, who is awaiting an
appeal on a death sentence handed down for treason.
	   On Saturday, Bockarie, one of the rebels' top generals, demanded
that Sierra Leone's President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah resign or the
rebels would storm and capture Freetown before the New Year.
	   ``Failure of Kabbah to resign, and we will start bombarding
Freetown and will not stop until victory is won,'' Bockarie told
The Associated Press.
	   That was a change from a day earlier when Bockarie demanded only
talks and Sankoh's release, or rebels would attack on New Year's
Day.
	   By late Friday a British-led evacuation had airlifted to 100
foreigners, mostly Britons, from Freetown to London and Senegal's
capital of Dakar. Many British citizens were expected to remain in
Freetown for the time being, a High Commission official said on
condition of anonymity.
	   The U.S. Embassy was expected to close soon, although only a
handful of staff were in the country and most Americans have been
advised to stay out of Sierra Leone for security reasons since
1997.
	   United Nations observer mission has withdrawn some of its
military observers in the interior to Freetown while non-essential
staff were evacuated to neighboring Guinea.
	   In a state radio broadcast, President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah's
government condemned the British airlift, saying it played into
rebel designs to spread panic.
	   The rebels are widely believed to have killed, maimed and raped
thousands of unarmed villagers in a revenge campaign against the
government aimed to spreading fear among the country's civilian
population.
	   (str-gam/ids)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
