r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Barbados-Elections 1stLd-Writethru   12-26 0364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Barbados-Elections, 1st Ld-Writethru,0370 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Minority party chooses not to participate in 1999 election
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with prime minister calling elections for Jan. 20;
EDITS throughout &QL; 
 &UR; By ERIC NURSE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRIDGETOWN, Barbados (AP) _ Prime Minister Owen Arthur called
elections for Jan. 20, 1999, the earliest date possible.
	   Arthur announced the elections Saturday in a radio address after
meeting with Governor General Sir Clifford Husbands.
	   Politicians of all three parties had expected Arthur to call
elections within the next few days at the latest.
	   ``The calling of elections is not a surprise and the nation is
ready,'' Arthur said in his brief comments.
	   Earlier Saturday, the leader of the minority National Democratic
Party announced it will not contest the elections.
	   In explaining his decision not to run, party leader Dr. Richie
Haynes cited a lack of resources and an inability to gain
additional seats or significantly affect the outcome of the vote.
Haynes is the party's sole member of Parliament.
	   The party, formed in 1989 by members disaffected with the
Democratic Labor Party, ``was not formed just to be another
power-seeking election machine, but as a party devoted to the
development and promotion of values,'' Haynes said.
	   With the economy in good shape, Arthur is expected to return for
another term as prime minister. His Barbados Labor Party currently
holds 18 seats while the opposition Democratic Labor Party holds
nine and Haynes fills the remaining seat.
	   Polls show Arthur's party leading and Haynes concurred. ``It is
clear the people of Barbados will give strong support to the
present government,'' he said.
	   University of the West Indies political science professor
Neville Duncan said Haynes' party did not have a credible shot at
becoming the main opposition party and was wise not to spend
limited resources on the election.
	   ``It was a sensible decision by Dr. Haynes and the NDP, given
the state of political play in Barbados today,'' said Duncan.
	   Haynes was finance minister for the Democratic party in the
1980s but broke away to form his own party in 1989. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
