</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Terrorist Pardoned </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Leftist terrorist pardoned by Italian president
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ A convicted Italian terrorist has left prison after
a Christmas Eve pardon by President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro, Italian
news reports said Saturday.
	   Giorgio Panizzari had served 28 years of a life sentence for
terrorism. He was one of the founders of the leftist terrorist
organization Armed Proletarian Nuclei, one of several domestic
terror groups that operated in Italy in the late 1960s, the 1970s
and early 1980s.
	   Among the crimes he claimed was the kidnapping of a judge. He
was one of the inmates the Red Brigades terrorist group tried in
vain to have freed in exchange for former Christian Democrat
Premier Aldo Moro, kidnapped in 1978. Moro was killed later that
year by his Red Brigades captors.
	   Italian heads of state occasionally issue pardons at holiday
time. Last year, Scalfaro pardoned six terrorists, five of them
leftists and the other a rightwing extremist.
	   (fd)
</TEXT>
