w2058 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Congo-Libya     12-26 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Congo-Libya </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Congolese rebels, Kabila meet Gadhafi in Tripoli
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By HRVOJE HRANJSKI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) _ Congolese President Laurent Kabila and the
rebels fighting to oust him on Saturday were in the Libyan capital,
Tripoli, where their host Moammar Gadhafi was acting as a peace
mediator in Congo's five-month war.
	   It wasn't immediately clear if Kabila met face-to-face with the
rebel leaders, Ernest Wamba dia Wamba and Bizima Karaha, although a
rebel source said the two sides were expected to engage in a series
of ``discrete'' meetings.
	   So far, Kabila's repeated refusal to meet the rebels has
torpedoed efforts to broker a cease-fire and open political
negotiations in Congo. Earlier in the week, African negotiators
postponed another round of peace talks originally scheduled for
Dec. 27-28 in Lusaka, Zambia.
	   Kabila is demanding the withdrawal from Congo of troops from
Rwanda and Uganda, who have supported the rebels since they took up
arms in August accusing Kabila of mismanagement, corruption and
ethnic warmongering. Zimbabwe, Angola, Namibia and Chad have sent
troops and arms on the government side.
	   The war appears headed for a stalemate in the vast Congolese
forests dotted by rivers and swamps where the Rwandan-backed rebels
took control of much of eastern Congo but faced resistance from
government-allied troops and aircraft.
	   A peace plan put forward by the Organization of African Unity
includes a cease-fire, withdrawal of foreign forces and talks on
the future of Congo.
	   Little was known about the meetings in Tripoli and officials on
both sides remained tightlipped.
	   Libyan TV on Friday reported on Kabila's arrival on Friday night
and a meeting with Gadhafi. It quoted Kabila as thanking Gadhafi
for his continuous efforts to contact ``all the parties to the
conflict in Congo with a view to reaching a peaceful solution to
this issue within an African framework.''
	   Gadhafi has supported Kabila and, according to Chadian press
reports, bankrolled the involvement of Chadian troops fighting on
Kabila's behalf in northern Congo.
	   The rebels _ a coalition of ethnic Tutsis, disaffected Congolese
soldiers and opposition politicians _ have in principle agreed to a
cease-fire but only if negotiated directly with Kabila.
	   Kabila, however, has maintained he is the victim of an outside
aggression and says he can negotiate only with Rwanda and Uganda.
	   Both countries, which installed Kabila in power in May 1997
after ousting former longtime dictator Mobutu Sese Seko, say they
will keep their troops in Congo as long as their security is
threatened.
	   Uganda and Rwanda accuse the Congolese president of enlisting
thousands of Rwandan and Ugandan rebels with bases eastern Congo.
	   (hh/gam) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
