<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 12/26/1998 12:16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2077 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Angola-BesiegedCity     12-26 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Angola-Besieged City </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Angolans in Kuito venture onto the streets amid rebel shelling on
</HEADLINE>
outskirts &QL; 
 &UR; By CRISTIANA PEREIRA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ People ventured out onto the streets of
Kuito on Saturday, avoiding the northern side of the besieged
Angolan city targeted by rebel artillery for a second day, a Roman
Catholic bishop said.
	   ``Today's a sunny day ... and people have come out for a walk,''
Bishop Jose Nambi said by phone from Kuito. ``They're taking the
risk.''
	   His voice was cheerful despite the tension in the central
highland city which has been the center of fighting between UNITA
rebels and the Angolan army for nearly a month.
	   Both sides have launched intense attacks throughout the central
highlands of the vast southwest African country for the past three
weeks, undermining a 1994 U.N.-brokered peace accord aimed at
ending a two-decade civil war.
	   Rebels on Saturday targeted the village of Cunji, overlooking
the northern outskirts of Kuito, which lies some 500 kilometers
(310 miles) southeast of the capital Luanda, Bishop Nambi said.
	   ``Yesterday and the day before we had serious problems,'' the
bishop said, referring to the heaviest rebel attack on Kuito in two
weeks in which thirty people were killed and 37 wounded.
	   Kuito's hospital, Bishop Nambi said, was functioning with hardly
any medicine and nurses and volunteers were taking in newly wounded
people, mostly civilians, every day.
	   Observers fear a humanitarian crisis as stocks run low. Relief
agencies have stopped flying to Kuito because the airport has been
targeted by rebel artillery to prevent the government sending in
reinforcements.
	   ``It's very tough for the displaced in terms of food. They left
everything behind, and there isn't enough medicine, or blankets to
go round,'' the bishop said.
	   The seminary where Bishop Nambi was speaking from has served as
shelter for part of the 30,000 displaced people that have poured
into Kuito. People have also taken refuge in the hospital, in
churches, abandoned houses, or simply under street balconies.
	   The November-April rainy season has also worsened the plight of
the some 130,000 people now in the city.
	   Kuito was reduced to rubble in a brutal year-long siege until
government forces ousted UNITA rebels in 1994, prior to the
U.N-brokered pact.
	   That period of war came after UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi
rejected his defeat in the country's first elections in 1992, which
both sides had agreed to in a previous peace agreement the year
before.
	   UNITA _ the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
_ began fighting against President Jose Eduardo dos Santos' ruling
MPLA party after the country's 1975 independence from Portugal.
	   The 1994 U.N.-brokered pact required UNITA to disarm and hand
over control of almost half the country of 10 million people to the
government.
	   UNITA claimed it had disarmed and demobilized its forces, under
U.N. supervision, over the past four years.
	   However, the rebels are estimated to have about 30,000 guerrilla
soldiers hidden in the bush, compared with the government's
100,000-strong army.
	   (cp/cg)	   
</TEXT>
