<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-British Roundup </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chelsea downed Saints to go temporarily top while Reds down Forest
</HEADLINE>
3-0 &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: will be updated by 2000 GMT after Blackburn-Villa game &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT MILLWARD &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Unbeaten since the opening day of the season,
Chelsea returned to the top of the Premier League with a 2-0
victory at struggling Southampton on Saturday although Aston Villa
had the chance to regain top place by beating Blackburn in an
evening match.
	   Norwegian striker Tore Andre Flo and Uruguayan midfielder
Gustavo Poyet scored the Blues' goals at The Dell. The result means
that Gianluca Vialli's team is unbeaten in 18 Premier League games
in a row.
	   Chelsea moved to the top on goal difference but Villa, which
kicked off six hours later, would regain its three-point lead by
winning at Blackburn.
	   After six games without a win, Manchester United revived its
title chances with a 3-0 win over last place Nottingham Forest at
Old Trafford.
	   Norwegian defender Ronny Johnsen scored the first two and Ryan
Giggs added the other.
	   Alan Shearer and Duncan Ferguson were together on the Newcastle
lineup for the first time since last month's arrival of Ferguson
from Everton had set up a 22 million pound (dlrs 36.74 million)
strikeforce.
	   But the Magpies tumbled 3-0 at home to fourth place Leeds, who
netted through Australian striker Harry Kewell, Lee Bowyer and
Dutch striker Jimmy Floyd Hasselbaink despite having several
players missing through injury.
	   Ian Wright returned to Highbury as a West Ham player but his new
team went down 1-0 after an early strike by the Gunners' Dutch
winger Marc Overmars to move up to fifth.
	   Liverpool ended Middlesbrough's nine-game unbeaten home record
by scoring a 3-1 win at the Riverside stadium with goals by Jamie
Carragher, Jamie Redknapp and Vegard Heggem. Brian Deane replied
for Boro from Paul Gascoigne's free kick but Bryan Robson's team
slipped to sixth.
	   A first half goal by veteran Tony Cottee earned Leicester a 1-0
win at Sheffield Wednesday while Everton and Derby ground out a 0-0
tie at Goodison Park.
	   Charlton, sliding down towards the relegation zone, went ahead
through Neal Redfearn's curling 25-meter shot at Selhurst Park but
Wimbledon hit back through Jason Euell and Michael Hughes for a 2-1
win.
	   All 20 teams will be in action on Monday or Tuesday before
getting involved in FA Cup games Jan. 2-3.
	   Division One leader Sunderland, which had an 11-point lead last
weekend, had that cut to five after losing 1-0 at Sunderland.
Second place Ipswich crushed Portsmouth 3-0.
	   Scottish Premier League leader Rangers struggled to a 1-0
victory over St. Johnstone while second place Kilmarnock, three
points behind, edged Hearts 1-0. Defending titlist Celtic, 10
points behind its Glasgow rival, visits Dundee on Sunday.
	   Scottish World Cup center-back Colin Hendry was sent off for
deliberate handball in the area but St. Johnstone's John O'Neil
fired the ensuing penalty kick against the bar and Rangers clinched
the three points through a goal by Italian defender Sergio Porrini
19 minutes from the end.
 &UR; MORE LATER
</TEXT>
