w2109 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Italy-PayTV-Murdoch     12-26 0333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Pay TV-Murdoch </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Italy's Telecom confirms deal with Murdoch, French TV
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MILAN, Italy (AP) _ Telecom Italian on Saturday confirmed that
it has reached an agreement in principle to sell up to 80 percent
of its digital pay TV unit to Rupert Murdoch's media empire.
	   On Thursday evening, Italy's ANSA news agency had reported that
the stakes would be sold to the Murdoch empire and to France's TF1.
	   ``The dialogue to include other partners, Italian and European,
is continuing, said a Telecom statement. In reaching the agreement,
both sides pledged to ``develop a digital pay TV offer of elevated
interest for the market, including transmissions of Italian major
league soccer games,'' the statement said.
	   The long-anticipated accord has been much debated in Italy,
where some in government and media have argued against foreign
ownership of the pay TV industry.
	   Murdoch was especially interested in the lucrative soccer
broadcast rights in Italy.
	   Telecom owns 100 percent of the pay television unit, Stream,
which has about 120,000 subscribers.
	   The Italian news agency AGI said the accord between Telecom and
NewsEurope Corp. was expected to be signed in early January.
	   Italy's undersecretary of communications, Vincenzo Vita,
expressed concern that the Italians wouldn't hold the majority
share.
	   Italian investors have been scared off by the high investments
the operation would need.
	   The accord would establish an alternative in Italy to pay-TV
network Tele Piu, which is 10 percent controlled by the media
empire of former Italian Premier Silvio Berlusconi.
	   Earlier in the month, Italy's state broadcaster RAI signed a
memorandum of understanding with France's pay-television Canal Plus
for the creation of a digital TV platform.
	   RAI's accord with Canal Plus seemed to indicate that the Italian
broadcaster would be a partner in the digital TV unit Stream, along
with Telecom Italia and New Corp.
	   (fd)
</TEXT>
