<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Prison Disturbance, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0319 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Five hostages free, but Mexican prison siege continues
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with five hostages now free; unknown number
still being held, one prisoner surrendering, negotiations
continuing. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Four hostages held by inmates at a Mexican
prison were freed Saturday and a fifth escaped, but a standoff
continued, authorities reported. One inmate surrendered.
	   The four inmates took hostages at the Reclusorio Sur prison
Friday afternoon after being foiled in an escape attempt, said
Jaime Alvarez Ramos, the city's director of prisons. News reports
said they have grenades and guns.
	   There were no reports of serious injuries.
	   Officials don't know the exact number of hostages, said a
spokesman for the prison system, speaking on condition of
anonymity. News reports gave varying figures, ranging from eight to
more than 20.
	   Four hostages were released over a three hour period Saturday
morning, the prison system said in a statement. They included two
prisoners, a 76-year-old woman and a pregnant woman who had been
visiting relatives in the prison.
	   A fifth hostage, a nurse, managed to escape.
	   One of the inmates holding hostages surrendered and negotiations
were continuing with the remaining three.
	   Alvarez and city police chief Alejandro Gertz had entered the
prison Friday evening to hear the inmates' demands for the release
of the hostages. Alvarez said that, for the moment, the captors
were only asking for cigarettes, food and water.
	   The hostages were reportedly being held in the prison infirmary
and medical personnel were among the captives.
	   The prison was filled with Christmas visitors at the time. About
200 adults and 150 children were gradually evacuated during the
day.
	   Hundreds of police continued to surround the prison Saturday.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
