<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sierra Leone-Glance,0370 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sierra Leone at a Glance
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   Facts about Sierra Leone:
	   ___
	   GEOGRAPHY: West African nation covering 28,680 square miles
(74,300 square kilometers); bound by Guinea to north and east,
Liberia to southeast and Atlantic Ocean to southwest. Tropical
climate.
	   PEOPLE: 4.7 million people; 30 percent of population from Temne
ethnic group in the north and Mende in the south. Other groups
include Krio, Lokko, Sherbo, Limba, Susu, Fulani and Kono.
	   LANGUAGES AND RELIGIONS: Official language is English, but
English derivative called Krio more widely spoken; there are 12
main tribal languages. 75 percent Muslim, 23 percent Christian and
2 percent animist and other.
	   HISTORY: Settled two centuries ago by freed slaves from Britain,
the United States and Jamaica. Britain ruled from 1808 until April
27, 1961.
	   GOVERNMENT: First elections in 1952. All People's Congress party
ruled from 1971-92, when Maj. Gen. Joseph Momoh was ousted as
president in a coup.
	   After about six years of intermittent fighting between
government and the rebel Revolutionary United Front that left more
than 10,000 dead, President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah was elected and
signed a peace treaty with the rebels in November 1996. But he was
ousted in a May 25, 1997 military coup with rebel support. Kabbah's
government returned to power 10 months later in March after the
ECOMOG Nigerian-led West African intervention force drove the junta
into the interior.
	   Since then, Kabbah has disbanded the military and empowered
ECOMOG and the Kamajor traditional militia to fight the rebels.
Hundreds of thousands of people have been left homeless and
thousands killed, maimed and raped by the rebels, who began a
counterattack campaign against key towns outside Freetown last
week.
	   LIVING STANDARDS AND NATURAL RESOURCES: The United Nations ranks
Sierra Leone as the world's least developed nation. Per capita
income is dlrs 171 a year; life expectancy, 34 years; infant
mortality rate, 164 per 1,000 live births. Although rich in
diamond, gold, bauxite and other mineral resources, mining has been
at a relative standstill since 1995 as a result of fighting.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sierra Leone-Glance; CT:i; 
