<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Brazil-Jail Break,0265 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
121 prisoners escape from three Sao Paulo police lockups
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) _ Taking advantage of lax holiday
vigilance, 121 prisoners escaped from three Sao Paulo police
lockups Saturday, Brazilian media reported.
	   At a police holding cell in the northern part of the city, 89
inmates escaped at dawn through a hole they had pounded through a
wall before climbing onto the jail roof and leaping to freedom. At
the time, not one guard was on duty, reported Globo TV News.
	   The Globo report couldn't immediately be confirmed; local police
confirmed the jailbreaks but said they had no details.
	   At the Santa Isabel jail, 22 escaped while 10 more escaped at
another police facility, police said.
	   Sao Paulo, Brazil's richest and most populous state, has the
most prisoners in the nation _ an estimated 70,000, about half of
whom are held in police lockups and jails, according to Human
Rights Watch.
	   In most cases, outbreaks are sparked by overcrowding and delays
in moving state inmates to prisons with more space. Sao Paulo jails
and lockups are often filled to three times their capacity, human
rights groups say.
	   ``These are holding cells that should be used for 5-6 hours and
not long-term detention,'' James Cavallaro, head of the Brazil
office of Human Rights Watch told The Associated Press on Saturday.
``It's a miracle that there aren't more escapes and riots.''
	   In 1997, Sao Paulo suffered the most rebellions and escape
attempts in jails and lockups than any other state _ 195.
</TEXT>
