<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Obit-Covelli </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Leader of Italian monarchists dies in Italy
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Alfredo Covelli, who founded a party of monarchists
in 1946, the year the country voted against continuing the Italian
monarchy, has died in Rome, Italian news reports said Saturday.
	   Covelli, 84, died on Friday. No cause of death was given.
	   Italians in a 1946 referendum voted to establish the present
republic. Corbelli's National Monarchical Party appealed to some of
the 11.5 million Italians who had voted in favor of keeping the
royal family.
	   In 1972, the party was folded into the neofascist Italian Social
Movement.
	   Covelli served for more than 30 years in the Italian Parliament.
	   President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro, in a condolence message, praised
Covelli's ``defense of the values of the human person and of all
that which inspires love for the country.''
	   There were no immediate details about funeral arrangements or
survivors.
	   (fd)
</TEXT>
