<HEADER>
w2174 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Italy-BedsheetEscape     12-26 0202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Bedsheet Escape </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Escape expert uses classic technique to flee Milan prison
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: Joan as first name for man is cq &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MILAN, Italy (AP) _ A Romanian convicted of murder used the
classic knotted bedsheet technique to escape from a Milan prison
when guards were short-staffed for Christmas.
	   The Italian news agency ANSA reported that guards noticed Joan
Ursut, who was serving a 21-year sentence at Opera prison for the
murder of an Italian gangster, missing about lunch time on Friday.
	   Fog hampered the search for the 40-year-old Romanian, who had
been at the prison since 1989. The poor visibility made it
impossible for police helicopters to join in the search, which used
officers and dogs on the ground, ANSA said.
	   The report said that Ursut, who was allowed to have some
movement around the prison, lowered himself out of window opposite
a section of surrounding outside wall where no guards were on duty,
apparently due to the shortage of help on Christmas.
	   According to reports from Sweden, Ursut escaped from jails in
that country twice.
	   A prisoner at a Rome jail recently used the knotted sheet
technique in a successful escape.
	   (fd-sto)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Italy-Bedsheet Escape; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
(REG:ENGL;)
