<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Arafat </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Egypt tells Israel to implement the Wye River accord
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo CAI-101

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ The Israeli government should implement the
Wye River peace accord because it signed it, Egypt's Foreign
Minister Amr Moussa said Saturday after a meeting between Egyptian
and Palestinian leaders.
	   ``We expect the United States to put pressure (on Israel) toward
implementing this agreement,'' especially the part concerning a
withdrawal of Israeli troops from the West Bank, Moussa said.
	   Speaking after a series of talks between Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, Moussa said the
Israeli handling of the agreement brokered by U.S. President Bill
Clinton in October had created a bad impression.
	   Israel's image, Moussa said, was one of ``when I negotiate, I
negotiate to waste time and, if I sign, don't believe that I will
implement and, when the time for implementation comes, we will
hinder it.''
	   ``The Israeli government is supposed to implement the Wye River
accord because it is the government that signed the agreement,''
the foreign minister said.
	   On Dec. 2, Israel announced it was freezing the accord because
of what it alleged were Palestinian violations. It also refused to
go ahead with scheduled troop pullbacks from the West Bank unless
the Palestinians met certain conditions, including foregoing a plan
to unilaterally declare a Palestinian state in May 1999.
	   On Saturday, Mubarak and Arafat met one-on-one and then held a
meeting accompanied by their officials. The two leaders also broke
their fast together after sunset. Muslims are currently fasting for
the holy month of Ramadan.
	   Neither of the leaders spoke after the talks, but Moussa quoted
Arafat as saying that a failure to implement the accord could
``disturb'' the peace process.
	   Moussa said that, at Mubarak's suggestion, further
Egyptian-Palestinian meetings would be held in Cairo Saturday at
official level.
	   The Palestinian Cabinet demanded Friday that Israel lift its
suspension of the accord, saying that the Israeli election campaign
was no reason to freeze the process.
 &UR; str-bm-jbm
</TEXT>
