<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Copa Mercosur-Cruzeiro-Palmeiras,0474 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Palmeiras beats Cruzeiro 3-1 to force third game in Mercosur Cup.
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JACK EPSTEIN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) _ Palmeiras beat a visibly tired Cruzeiro
3-1 Saturday, forcing a third and decisive game in the first
Mercosur Cup championship final before a partisan crowd at Parque
Antartica stadium.
	   Cruzeiro, which won the first-leg game 2-1, needed only a tie to
capture the title, while Palmeiras had to win to force a final
game. The final will take place Tuesday, also at Parque Antartica.
	   Just last Wednesday, Cruzeiro lost the 1998 Brazilian
Championship 2-0 to the Corinthians in the third-leg of a hard
fought series. The devastating loss _ coupled with an earlier
setback this year in the finals of the Brazil Cup _ caused the
Brazilian media to speculate whether Cruzeiro had anything left.
	   ``Sadness could defeat Cruzeiro,'' said a headline in a Rio
newspaper.
	   But any sadness quickly turned to joy during Saturday's game, at
least initially, when defender Gilberto made a spectacular pass in
front of the net to striker Muller, who was fouled by Palmeiras
goalie Velloso. Striker Fabio Junior then scored on a penalty kick
in just the 2nd minute of play.
	   Palmeiras, however, came back after fullback Cleber took a pass
from Paraguayan defender Arce and scored in the 9th minute with a
head shot past Cruzeiro goalie Dida.
	   For the rest of the first half, a more rested Palmeiras, whose
lineup is laden with current and former members of the Brazilian
national team, kept up a relentless attack against a sluggish
Cruzeiro.
	   To be sure, Cruzeiro was playing in its 80th game of the season
and had not trained since losing last week's title game. Palmeiras,
on the other hand, had been practicing daily since its loss to
Cruzeiro in the opening game.
	   In the second half, Palmeiras striker Oseas scored with the
left-footed shot into the net in the 52nd minute. Soon afterwards,
Cleber was carried off on a stretcher after suffering a leg injury.
	   At the 86th minute, striker Paulo Nunes took a corner kick and
scored with a head shot past Cruzeiro goalie Dida. Nunes then
celebrated with the partisan crowd by donning a green Santa Claus
hat and wiggling with several teammates in an impromptu dance.
	   Despite his team's lackluster play Saturday, Cruzeiro head coach
Levir Culpi says his players will be ready on Tuesday.
	   ``For the past two months, every game has been a life and death
situation, and that has taken a heavy psychological toll,'' he told
reporters. '' But winning the Mercosur Cup is a question of
honor.''
	   It's also a question of finances. The winning team will receive
a record amount of dlrs 3.9 million ( 4.7 million reais) from the
South American Soccer Confederation.
</TEXT>
