<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Prison Disturbance, 4th Ld-Writethru,0371 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mexican prisoners release hostages and surrender
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with details from news conference,
officials now saying 19 hostages held, one prisoner captured Friday
night. ADDS byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By ADOLFO GARZA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Two Mexican prisoners released the remaining
14 hostages they had held for than 20 hours and surrendered
Saturday, officials said.
	   The siege at the Reclusorio Sur prison ended peacefully shortly
after noon, Jaime Alvarez Ramos, the city's director of prisons,
said at a news conference.
	   According to officials, four inmates, hoping to escape, started
a riot Friday afternoon while the prison was filled with Christmas
visitors.
	   When the escape was foiled, they took 19 hostages in the
infirmary: 11 inmates, four medical workers and four visitors.
	   ``It was a very regrettable event,'' Alvarez said. ``It wasn't
their plan to take hostages.''
	   The four prisoners were all serving time for violent crimes.
They were armed with three pistols, a rifle and a hand grenade,
Alvarez said.
	   Officials were investigating how they got the weapons.
	   The prisoners wanted to leave the country and were demanding an
armored truck and a plane to take them to Cuba, Alvarez said. They
had also asked for cigarettes, food and water.
	   One inmate was captured Friday night and another surrendered
Saturday morning, he said.
	   Over the next several hours, four hostages were freed and a
fifth, a nurse, escaped. Those released were a 76-year-old woman
and a pregnant woman who had been visiting relatives in the prison,
and two prisoners who had been held hostage.
	   Three police commanders negotiated with the two remaining
hostage-takers and persuaded one of them to surrender and to talk
his partner into giving up as well, Alvarez said. He did not say
why the prisoners decided to surrender.
	   All four will face charges from the riot and hostage-taking, he
said.
	   There were no reports of serious injuries, although one
prisoner, who was not involved in the hostage-taking, suffered an
eye injury during the riot, Alvarez said. 	   
</TEXT>
