<SLUG> BC-Britain-Bad Weather </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two likely dead as gales, rain lash Britain and Ireland
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Police in Britain and Ireland said Saturday that
two people were feared dead and several others injured as both
countries were battered by high wind, rain and snow.
	   Police said one man was killed in County Galway, western
Ireland, when a falling tree crushed his car.
	   In Brighton, southern England, coastguard said that one man was
swept into the sea by a 30 foot (9 meter) wave as he walked along
beach with his girlfriend and a child. A rescue attempt later
failed to winch him to safety.
	   Neither police force immediately gave identities for the men.
	   Elsewhere in Britain, the governmental Environment Agency issued
50 flood warnings after winds up to 100 miles (160 km) per hour and
heavy rainfall lashed parts of western Britain. In Scotland, snows
closed roads.
	   ``Environmental Agency staff have been working throughout
Christmas Day ... and we have currently got 50 flood warnings
out,'' said an agency spokesman speaking on terms of customary
anonymity.
	   In British-governed Northern Ireland, several people needed
treatment for minor injuries after gales lifted the roof off a
three-story block of flats in County Down, in the eastern part of
the province.
	   In southwestern Ireland, floods and fallen electricity and
telephone poles blocked roads.
	   (rs)
</TEXT>
