<SLUG> BC-Sports-Yachting-Sydney-Hobart, 2nd Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Several dropouts in annual race
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDs: recasts with early Sunday positions, changes headline &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Sydney maxi Marchioness on Monday
joined a list of high-profile retirees early on the second day of
the Sydney to Hobart yacht race.
	   Marchioness, which led with American yacht Sayonara and
Brindabella on Saturday night, was forced out with rig damage off
Eden on the New South Wales state south coast. Australian maxi Wild
Thing pulled out a few hours later with similar problems.
	   Six of the 115-fleet are out of the race, with 38-footer King
Billy also pulling out after damaging its rudder to join ABN AMRO
Challenge, Sydney and Sledgehammer back in port.
	   At the front, maxis Brindabella and Sayonara were within sight
of each other near Gabo Island and about to enter Bass Strait for
the journey to island state of Tasmania and its capital Hobart.
	   Challenge Again has resumed racing after recovering a crew
member earlier lost overboard.
	   The leading boats were traveling at 15 knots and well inside the
1996 race record set by German maxi Morning Glory of 2 days, 14
hours, 7 minutes and 10 seconds.
	   On Saturday, a crowd of about 300,000 people on the Sydney
headlands and harbor witnessed the start of the annual blue-water
classic. (djp) 	   
</TEXT>
