<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinians, 1st Ld-Writethru,0421 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede HEBRON, West Bank
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Netanyahu denies elections are stalling peace pact &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with Netanyahu comments and Arafat's
meeting with Mubarak; CHANGES byline and dateline. &QL; 
 &UR; By SARI BASHI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on
Saturday denied Palestinian charges that he had suspended the Wye
River peace accord because of upcoming elections, saying the
Palestinians were responsible for the freeze.
	   Netanyahu told Israel Radio he would implement the 2-month-old
U.S.-brokered accord once the Palestinians did their part,
including collecting illegal weapons held by Palestinian police and
civilians.
	   Netanyahu criticized the Palestinian Authority for releasing
Hamas spiritual leader Sheik Ahmed Yassin from house arrest
Wednesday, and for the escape from a Nablus jail earlier this week
of Jamil Jidala, a Palestinian jailed for killing two Israelis.
	   On Dec. 2, Israel announced it was freezing the accord because
of what it alleged were Palestinian violations. It also refused to
go ahead with promised troop pullbacks from the West Bank unless
the Palestinians met a series of conditions, including renouncing
plans to declare statehood in May.
	   The Palestinians have suggested that early elections for prime
minister, triggered by lawmakers' rejection of Netanyahu's peace
policies, were responsible for the freeze. How the peace pact
should be implemented _ or whether it should be implemented at all
_ is already a major campaign issue in the elections, expected by
late April.
	   Speaking after Friday night's meeting of the Palestinian Cabinet
in the West Bank town of Hebron, chief Palestinian negotiator Saeb
Erekat said the Israeli government was still responsible for
carrying out its commitments under the accord.
	   The Palestinian Cabinet said in a statement following the
meeting that it would continue making preparations for a statehood
declaration in May. The Palestinians also said they would seek help
from the Arab world and the rest of the international community
over the freezing of the peace process.
	   The Palestinian Cabinet called Israeli noncompliance with the
accord a ``dangerous development which was initiated by the Israeli
government without any reason besides its rejection of peace.''
	   Meanwhile, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat met with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak in Cairo on Saturday to discuss the frozen
agreement.
</TEXT>
