<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinians, 2nd Ld,0201 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Netanyahu denies elections are stalling peace pact
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES in grafs 3-4 with quotes from Egypt's foreign minister
after meeting Arafat. &QL; 
 &UR; By SARI BASHI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on
Saturday denied Palestinian charges that he had suspended the Wye
River peace accord because of upcoming elections, saying the
Palestinians were responsible for the freeze.
	   Netanyahu told Israel Radio he would implement the 2-month-old
U.S.-brokered accord once the Palestinians did their part,
including collecting illegal weapons held by Palestinian police and
civilians.
	   Egypt's Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said Saturday he expects the
United States to put pressure on Israel to implement the agreement,
especially the withdrawal of Israeli troops from the West Bank.
	   ``The Israeli government is supposed to implement the Wye River
accord because it is the government that signed the agreement,''
Moussa told reporters in Cairo after talks between Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
