<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-New Zealand-India </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New Zealand 132 for three at lunch on the second day
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) _ India dropped four catches but
took two crucial wickets in New Zealand's run chase on day two of
their test match at Basin Reserve on Sunday.
	   After India had been shot out for 208 on the first day, New
Zealand resuming on 52 for one, progressed to 132 for three at
lunch on the second day.
	   Leg spinner Anil Kumble produced a crucial blow before the
break, removing an obdurate Matthew Horne, who scored 38 runs in
190 minutes.
	   Horne and skipper Stephen Fleming (42) continued where they left
off Saturday in the second wicket stand, extending it to 72 before
disaster struck.
	   The pair came together after test debutant Matthew Bell was
dismissed for four on the first evening.
	   Fleming, who had batted faultlessly for almost two hours was
needlessly run out going for a second run which was never on.
	   Fleming failed to beat an Ajay Jadeja throw from square leg and
New Zealand was 79 for two in the 46th over.
	   New Zealand would have been in further trouble hadn't the
Indians grassed four catches, three of them by vice-captain Jadeja.
	   Horne dropped on 22 and 27 was finally beaten by a Kumble top
spinner that hurried on the opener and bowled him.
	   Craig McMillan dropped by Jadeja at short leg off Kumble was
unbeaten on 13 while an out-of-form Nathan Astle has batted for 80
minutes for his unbeaten 20 runs.
 &UR; (ik-tjh)
</TEXT>
