w2316 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PeopleandPlaces     12-26 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-People and Places,0699 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
People and places in the news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Includes items on the Arc de Triomphe, singer James Brown, a
luxury car's forgetful computer, Pope John Paul II, Taco Bell's
Chihuahua; some items have moved as separates. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Holiday visitors were barred from entering the Arc
de Triomphe on Saturday, after museum attendants there walked off
the job to demand the government hire more staff, officials said.
	   The strike that began Saturday morning was expected to last
through the weekend and into the following week, pending talks
between unions and the Culture Ministry, a ministry spokesman said.
	   Like employees at other Paris museums in recent weeks, the staff
went on strike to press the government to hire more employees to
keep up with a rising number of visitors, the spokesman said on
condition of anonymity.
	   Employees have also complained that conditions were more
difficult than at other Paris cultural sites, due to the noise and
pollution from the traffic circle surrounding the monument and the
cramped spaces inside the Arc, the spokesman said.
	   Officials expected to reach an agreement early in the week, he
said. Union officials could not be reached for comment.
	    &UR; ___
	   AUGUSTA, Georgia (AP) _ The Godfather of Soul is feeling more
like a grandfather these days.
	   ``I got an upper plate put in,'' James Brown said during his
sixth annual Christmas Party. ``I used to have a gap between my
front teeth. Now that that's gone, I can't hit the high notes. I
lost two octaves.''
	   However, the 65-year-old singer claimed at his midweek party in
Augusta that he can still do on-stage splits.
	   ``But I don't have to,'' he said.
	    &UR; ___
	   POTSDAM, Germany (AP) _ A German couple out for a Christmas
drive near Berlin ended up in a river _ apparently because their
luxury car's computer forgot to mention they had to wait for a
ferry.
	   The 57-year-old driver and his passenger were not injured in the
accident, police said Saturday.
	   Several companies sell computer navigators, some of which are
attached to dashboards and serve as electronic road maps. Some
offer traffic updates and Internet connections.
	   The German couple was out driving Friday night when they came to
a ferry crossing at the Havel River in Caputh, six miles from
Berlin.
	   That information, however, was never stored in the
satellite-steered navigation system they were using, police said.
The driver kept going straight in the dark, expecting a bridge, and
ended up in the water.
	   River traffic was stopped for two hours while the car was fished
out about 4 meters (13 feet) from the river bank.
	   ``You can't always blindly rely on technology,'' a coast guard
police officer said.
	    &UR; ___
	   CASTEL GANDOLFO, Italy (AP) _ After a bout with the flu and the
demands of Christmas appearances, Pope John Paul II bantered with
pilgrims Saturday as he began a brief holiday southeast of Rome.
	   John Paul scheduled a late morning helicopter flight Saturday
for Castel Gandolfo, a lakeside town where he will spend his
holiday break.
	   The pope, who is to spend a few days in the town, seemed rested
and in good spirits in the crisp, sunny day. Last week, the Vatican
announced that the pope had canceled some private audiences because
of a light flu and fever.
	   On Christmas Eve, the pope celebrated midnight Mass, which
lasted into the early hours of the next day. He also addressed the
public gathered in St. Peter's Square at noon on Christmas Day.
	    &UR; ___
	   IRVINE, California (AP) _ Taco Bell's Chihuahua is one hot dog.
	   So far, consumers have bought 13 million promotional plush toys
modeled on the pop-eyed TV mascot, and the Irvine-based fast-food
chain has ordered another 10 million at up to dlrs 3.99 each.
	   ``Everybody I know wants them,'' said Trasia Barnes, whose
9-year-old daughter, Shannon Bloom, owns a Chihuahua that gives the
Christmas greeting ``Feliz Navidad, amigos.''
	   Three other versions repeat catch phrases from the TV
commercials: ``Yo quiero Taco Bell,'' ``Viva gorditas'' and ``Here,
lizard, lizard'' _ which the pooch says as he tries to trap
Godzilla in a tie-in with the movie.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-People and Places; CT:i; 
