<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0651 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of news from The Associated Press. Some items have
moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f'' category
codes:
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq _ Iraq will fire on U.S. and British warplanes
patrolling the no-fly zones that the United States and its allies
imposed after the Gulf War, Iraq's vice president said Saturday.
Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadan told Qatar's Al-Jazeera
television that Iraq would not allow the flights of U.S. and
British aircraft in the zones over northern and southern Iraq. The
United States, Britain and France set up the no-fly zones in
1991-92 to halt air attacks against Kurdish rebels in the north and
Shiite Muslim rebels in the south. U.S. officials said say they
will continue to enforce the no-fly zone. ``Our pilots can act in
self-defense if they feel threatened at any time,'' said National
Security Council spokesman P. J. Crowley. (IRAQ)
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ The defections of two key Khmer
Rouge guerrilla leaders Saturday left only the brutal, one-legged
general Ta Mok holding out in Cambodian jungles. Known as ``The
Butcher,'' Ta Mok is hiding with less than 100 die-hard loyalists,
said a military official in Thailand, which closely monitors Khmer
Rouge activities. ``The Cambodian government's attitude is to let
him (Ta Mok) grow old and die by himself. It's not worth the money
to chase him,'' Thai Maj. Gen Wiwat Sattarak said. The two Khmer
Rouge leaders who defected to the Cambodian government included
Khieu Samphan, who for decades posed as a moderate front man for a
gang counted among history's worst killers. The other leader was
Nuon Chea, once the second-in-command to the late Khmer Rouge
leader Pol Pot. (CAMBODIA-KHMER ROUGE)
	   UNITED NATIONS _ A U.N. aircraft with 14 people on board
reportedly crashed in Angola Saturday in an area where heavy
fighting was continuing between UNITA rebels and government forces,
a U.N. spokesman said. There was no word on whether the four crew
members and 10 passengers had survived. There was also no immediate
information on whether the plane was shot down or suffered
mechanical failure. The Portuguese news agency Lusa said the
aircraft burst into flames shortly after take-off from Huambo, some
500 kilometers (310 miles) southeast of the capital Luanda, and
crashed 40 kilometers (25 miles) away in Vila Nova.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan urged the Angolan government and UNITA
to allow members of the U.N. Observer Mission to go to the scene to
assist in search and rescue operations. (UN-ANGOLA)
	   LAPASTICA, Yugoslavia _ Hundreds of refugees fleeing renewed
fighting in northern Kosovo congregated Saturday in a regional
ethnic Albanian guerrilla stronghold, crowding into houses by the
dozens to escape bitterly cold weather. After a two-day crackdown
by Serb police and Yugoslav army units, most refugees in the area
west of Podujevo made their way to Lapastica, a village still held
by the Kosovo Liberation Army. A Serb farmer was killed near
Podujevo and Albanian sources reported a police attack in the same
region. (YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO)
	   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on Saturday denied
Palestinian charges that he suspended the Wye River peace accord
because of upcoming elections, saying that Palestinian
noncompliance is responsible for the freeze. Netanyahu told Israel
Radio that he would implement the 2-month old U.S.-brokered accord
once the Palestinians did their part, including collecting illegal
weapons held by Palestinian police and civilians. The Israeli
president criticized the Palestinian Authority for releasing Hamas
spiritual leader Sheik Ahmed Yassin from house arrest on Wednesday
and permitting a Palestinian jailed for killing two Israelis to
have ``passed through the revolving door, exited, and escaped
outside,'' the radio said. (ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS)
</TEXT>
