w2322 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LatinAmericanBriefs     12-26 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Latin American Briefs,0641 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
have moved separately
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items from Brazil, Argentina and Mexico. Some items
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) _ Shootouts between drug traffickers
and police in two shantytowns left five people dead, including a
gang leader, police said Saturday.
	   The violence began after police arrived at the Cerro Cora slum
to investigate gunfire at a local dance and were shot at by
traffickers who control the slum's drug trade, police said.
	   The confrontation continued into nearby Pereirao slum for
another two hours and ended with the death of gang leader Claudio
Passos da Rocha and four other traffickers.
	   In the aftermath, police seized several machine guns, pistols
and large quantities of marijuana.
	   Drug traffickers control Rio's estimated 600 slums. As a result,
many police are afraid to enter slums.
	   ___
	   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) _ An Argentine federal judge has
asked Syria to extradite a former customs director at Buenos Aires'
international airport to stand trial on charges of money
laundering.
	   The Buenos Aires daily newspaper Clarin on Saturday quoted
Argentina's ambassador to Syria, Juan Pardo Argerich, as saying he
relayed the request 20 days ago for the extradition of Ibrahim al
Ibrahim.
	   Ibrahim, a Syrian citizen and former brother-in-law of Argentine
President Carlos Menem, was named director of customs at Ezeiza
International Airport in 1989.
	   A year later, a drug trafficker arrested in Spain told a judge
that Ibrahim and his then-wife Amira Yoma, sister of former
Argentine first lady Zulema Yoma, were part of a gang of money
launderers.
	   Ibrahim fled the country in 1992 using a forged passport.
	   ___
	   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) _ Taking advantage of lax holiday
vigilance, prisoners escaped from three Sao Paulo police lockups
Saturday, the Brazilian media reported.
	   At a police holding cell in the northern part of the city, 89
inmates escaped at dawn through a hole they had pounded through a
wall before climbing onto the jail roof and leaping to freedom.
	   At the time, not one guard was on duty, reported Globo TV News.
	   Twenty-two prisoners escaped from the Santa Isabel jail, while
10 more escaped from another police facility.
	   Sao Paulo, Brazil's richest and most populous state, has the
nation's most prisoners _ some 70,000 _ of whom 30,000 are held in
police lockups and jails, according to Human Rights Watch.
	   In most cases, outbreaks are caused by overcrowding.
	   Brazil's prisons are usually full, so authorities send convicts
to jails or lockups meant to hold suspects awaiting trial for a
short time. It is not uncommon for such lockups to have 200 people
in a space designed for 40, human rights groups say.
	   ___
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Mexican authorities said Saturday they have
arrested a U.S. insurance company executive accused of
participating in a bankruptcy fraud scheme in Oklahoma.
	   Donald Phillip Havenar was arrested in the northwestern city of
Hermosillo, Sonora, outside an insurance business he owned,
Servicios Administrativos de la Frontera de R.L de C.V., the
Mexican attorney general's office said in a statement.
	   It did not say when the arrest took place.
	   Havenar, chief executive officer and president of First
Assurance and Casualty Co. Ltd, is one of five executives accused
of diverting nearly dlrs 7 million in policyholder payments to
themselves and companies they controlled.
	   The defendants allegedly sold insurance policies through First
Assurance but did not maintain enough funds to pay claims.
	   The other four suspects have pleaded innocent.
	   Havenar was transferred to a prison in Mexico City to facing
extradition proceedings.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Latin American Briefs; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
