<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 12/26/1998 19:26:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2325 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Ireland-Obit-Goulding     12-26 0304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ireland-Obit-Goulding </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former IRA chief of staff dies aged 75
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) _ Cathal Goulding, former chief of staff of
the Irish Republican Army, died in a Dublin hospital Saturday aged
75, Britain's national news agency, Press Association, has
reported.
	   A cause of death, and funeral details, were not immediately
known.
	   Goulding, a committed Marxist, was the IRA's commander in 1969
when the paramilitary group split.
	   Goulding's poorly armed and organized IRA was unwilling to
launch insurrection in British-ruled Northern Ireland in the late
1960s, and after a bloody feud younger Catholic militants such as
Gerry Adams and Martin McGuinness broke away to form the
``Provisional'' IRA and Sinn Fein.
	   Under Goulding's direction Official IRA called a ceasefire in
1972. He became highly critical of the ''Provisionals,'' saying
that violence in Northern Ireland was sectarian, and made Irish
unity more difficult.
	   Gouldling was born in Dublin in 1922 from a family with strong
IRA links, and was interned by the Irish government during World
War II for his membership of the group. He was involved in the
revival of the organization after 1945, and in 1953 was jailed for
eight years in Britain for an arms raid on a school in England.
	   After its ceasefire, the Official IRA was involved in feuds with
other anti-British militant gangs such as the Irish National
Liberation Army, after that small but violent group shot dead an
Official IRA member in February 1975.
	   Today, the Official IRA is affiliated with the Workers' Party,
and has a small number of gunmen running rackets in Catholic parts
of Belfast.
	   Goulding was also a member of the Workers' Party ruling
executive, eventually formed by the ``official'' arm of Sinn Fein.
	   (rs)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
