<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-US-Civil Action,0599 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`Civil Action' lawyer has moved on in life
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With ARTS-Film Review-Civil Action &QL; 
 &UR; By TOM KIRCHOFER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BOSTON (AP) _ As a young lawyer in the early 1980s, Jan
Schlichtmann wore dlrs 1,000 suits, drove a late model Porsche and
took what he now recognizes as unnecessary risks as he fought for
justice.
	   It was a game of win or lose, and in representing clients
injured in accidents, he passed up reasonable settlement offers
from defendants to gamble on getting bigger paybacks from juries.
	   But then a case landed on his desk that shattered his finances,
nearly cost him his sanity and ultimately led him to realize that
there is a better way to practice law.
	   That case involved children in Woburn who were dying of
leukemia; parents suspected drinking water wells had been
contaminated with industrial waste. Schlichtmann took their case
and sued two corporate behemoths. As he put it, ``Woburn was a
war.''
	   The story of the courtroom showdown became the subject of the
best-selling book, ``A Civil Action.'' It comes to the big screen
this month as a Touchstone Pictures film, with John Travolta
starring as Schlichtmann.
	   ``Woburn was a defining moment in my life,'' Schlichtmann said.
``I came out with a whole different way of looking at the world
which has fundamentally changed me as a human being and as a
lawyer.''
	   The case pitted Schlichtmann and the parents of several children
killed by leukemia against Beatrice Foods and multinational
chemical corporation W.R. Grace, which were accused of improperly
disposing of toxins.
	   Schlichtmann's colleagues warned him the case was a ``black
hole,'' but he pursued it for more than five years. It consumed
him, leaving both him and his firm bankrupt.
	   A jury never found the companies liable. Beatrice was let off
the hook, and W.R. Grace settled with the families for dlrs 8
million, but the company never admitted any wrongdoing.
	   ``I realize now that while that would have been nice, there are
more sustaining victories,'' he said. ``The greatest victories are
those that can be shared with everyone.''
	   Schlichtmann, 47, still takes environmental cases. He is now
representing 60 families in Toms River, New Jersey, who believe
their water was contaminated by two companies, causing a cluster of
cancer cases.
	   A woman from Toms River contacted him after reading ``A Civil
Action,'' but he says he is approaching the latest case in a much
different way.
	   ``We went and knocked on the doors of the lawyers for the
companies,'' he said. ``We would try and be cooperative, in the
hopes that by the sharing of information, we'll all be able to help
each other.''
	   And he says the strategy seems to be working. The parties agreed
to an 18-month moratorium on lawsuits as they work toward an
agreement.
	   While today's Schlichtmann still has a fiery intensity and
speaks passionately about his belief in the law and the pursuit of
truth, he seems to have mellowed with age.
	   Schlichtmann, 47, drives a station wagon with two car seats in
the back to chauffeur around his sons, 3-year-old Max and
2-year-old Zak. His Porsche was repossessed during the Woburn case.
	   He lives with the boys and his wife, Claudia, in Beverly and
seems far removed from the flashy young lawyer he once was.
	   ``I loved life. I was successful, I liked my profession. I had
great confidence in my talents and abilities,'' he said. ``I liked
representing people, and if I won, being well paid for it. I liked
all the things that money could buy.''
</TEXT>
