<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Australia-England </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Stewart digs in against Australia
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) _ England captain Alec Stewart made
the most of his return as an opening batsman by taking the fight up
to Australia on the second day of the fourth cricket test at the
MCG on Sunday.
	   Stewart watched his team slump to four for two wickets in the
third over but scored an unbeaten 78 in a first session extended by
30 minutes after Saturday's opening day was washed out.
	   At lunch, England was 127 for three with Mark Ramprakash on 19.
	   With England 2-0 down with two games to play in the series,
Stewart gave up the wicketkeeping gloves to give a debut to Warren
Hegg. The decision allowed him to reunite with Mike Atherton at the
top of the order.
	   Their union lasted just five balls before Atherton (0) fell to
Glenn McGrath for the 10th time in his past 19 innings against the
Australians.
	   Atherton was clearly upset by the decision after he was given
out edging through to Ian Healy.
	   McGrath struck again in his next over when No. 3 Mark Butcher
(0) played forward and nicked an inside edge onto his front pad and
Justin Langer snared a sharp catch at short leg.
	   Stewart played a positive innings, hooking and pulling strongly
whenever the Australians dropped short.
	   He brought up his 50 off just 66 balls, slapping a full toss
from leg-spinner Stuart MacGill down the ground for four.
	   Stewart put on 77 with Nasser Hussain (19) before the No.4 gave
Matthew Nicholson a first test wicket on debut.
	   Nicholson was smashed for 11 off his opening over but recovered
in his fifth to get an edge from Hussain which gave world
record-holder Healy his 350th test dismissal.
	   Australian captain Mark Taylor won the toss Saturday before the
entire day's play was lost and the pitch appeared to be settling
into a good batting strip. An extra half hour will be added to the
start and finish of each day to make up for lost time.
 &UR; (tjh)
