<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-Australia-Movies, 1st Add,0181 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYDNEY: Film Commission.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   Almost Australian dollars 500 million (U.S. dlrs 315 million)
was spent on production and post production services for the year
to the end of June 1998, up from Australian dollars 410 million
(U.S. dlrs 258 million) in 1996-97 and Australian dollars 375
million (U.S. dlrs 236 million) the year before.
	   The boom in production follows an influx of Australians into
mainstream film making _ most obviously the Oscars won by ``Shine''
star Geoffrey Rush and ``Babe'' director George Miller.
	   Australian faces such as those of actors Rush, Russell Crow and
Cate Blanchett and directors Miller, Philip Noyce and Peter Weir
are no longer strangers to Hollywood. Newcomers such as Baz
Luhrmann, director of ``William Shakespeare's Romeo and Juliet,''
and ``Dark City's'' Alex Proyas may be seen as a second wave.
	   Some local filmmakers, however, fear greater numbers of big
overseas productions will shut out local producers by pushing up
costs and draining the talent pool of local crews.
</TEXT>
