<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-Country 1998, 1st Add,0203 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASHVILLE: wears on.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   Among the early treats of 1999 will be a new album from
Nashville outlaw Steve Earle, backed by a bluegrass band. It would
be interesting to see what happens if a record like that gets even
a small percentage of the marketing thought and promotional dollars
Brooks routinely demands and receives.
	   Some help from radio may come soon, speculates Jeff Walker,
president of Aristo Media, a Nashville company that does marketing
and publicity, and promotes songs to country music radio stations.
	   Walker thinks it's a matter of time before album-orientated
country radio stations start to appear in cities where the same
owner has more than one country music station. That could give
deserving artists like Earle and Lucinda Williams more airplay.
	   ``Album-orientated rock is certainly one of the main reasons pop
music got relaunched,'' Walker said. ``I can't see why in some
markets where there's two and three country stations, why they all
have to play this young, hit-driven hot country format ... .
	   ``We've plateaued and perhaps we've even come down a notch or
two. So it's time to roll up the sleeves now and be creative.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-ARTS-Country 1998, 1st Add; CT:i; 
