<SLUG> BC-Colombia-Arrests,0218 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Brothers arrested in 1997 execution of human rights couple
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) _ Two brothers were arrested Saturday in
connection with the 1997 slayings of two human rights workers and
one worker's father.
	   Juan Carlos and Fernando Gonzalez were captured in Medellin,
Colombia's second-largest city, and charged in the execution-style
killings of Mario Calderon, Elsa Alvarado and her father, Carlos
Alvarado, said police operations chief Gen. Alfredo Salgado.
	   The couple was killed along with Alvarado's father in their
Bogota apartment in May 1997 by hitmen suspected of working for a
right-wing paramilitary group.
	   The gunmen gained entry posing as federal agents, then forced
the victims to kneel on the floor before spraying them with
machine-gun fire. The woman's mother survived eight gunshot wounds,
and the couple's 18-month-old son escaped injury by hiding in a
closet.
	   Calderon, a former Jesuit priest, and Alvarado worked at the
Center for Research and Popular Education, a nongovernmental
organization that promotes peace and human rights.
	   Their murders, followed by the killings this year of two other
prominent rights workers, prompted outrage and government promises
to crack down on the right-wing militias.
</TEXT>
