w2468 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTS-Taiwan-Indigenou     12-26 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-Taiwan-Indigenous Voices,0791 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taiwan's indigenous people hit right notes in music business
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo NY198 &QL; 
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER BODEEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ As a reigning pop diva, Chang Hui-mei must
fight to keep her private life private. But when asked about her
childhood in an indigenous tribal village, her wariness dissolves
into a wide smile.
	   ``I've always considered myself lucky that I could not only be a
singer, but also that my personal background could permit more
people to understand indigenous people,'' Chang says. ``I think
that's great.''
	   Chang comes from a new generation of musicians from Taiwan's
indigenous tribes finding success in the island's entertainment
business _ and highlighting the vibrancy of this island's native
non-Chinese culture.
	   Indigenous performers have emerged as chart favorites in a
variety of musical styles _ from traditional vocal music to Chang's
dance records and the modern rock of Chang Chen-yueh and Power
Station.
	   And though they sing in the dominant Mandarin Chinese dialect
spoken throughout Taiwan, the natural ease and depth of emotion of
their performances sets them apart from the island's overwhelming
Chinese majority, music critics say.
	   They're also selling millions of records _ in Taiwan and
throughout the Chinese-speaking world.
	   ``Indigenous people, when they sing, when they dance, when
they're making music, it's a very natural feeling,'' said Landy
Chang, president of Magic Stone Records, which features several
indigenous singers in its lineup.
	   Ethnic Chinese tend to be more stilted in their performances, he
said.
	   Singing and dancing were a natural extension of Puyuma tribal
life in southeastern Taitung county, says Chang, the island's
undisputed top female star who mixes aboriginal chants into her
trademark pop.
	   ``People think I took years of lessons, but everything you see
on stage is what I learned growing up,'' she said in an interview
conducted between takes of her new music video.
	   Though tribal music has long been a fixture in Taiwan's music
scene, being an aboriginal performer has never carried such cachet.
The recent surge of interest in indigenous singers may be the
result of an an accident of licensing, critics say.
	   The German group Enigma's 1995 hit ``Return to Innocence''
lifted a recording of a melody sung by Amis tribesman Difang that
popularized indigenous music in a modern format _ though Difang
didn't know of his new-found fame until a friend heard the song on
the radio.
	   Lawyers for Difang, a 76-year-old farmer from Taitung, are now
fighting for a share of the royalties, while his own album of
traditional chants set to a world music beat has won steady record
sales and critical praise.
	   Taiwan's tribal music can also be heard on numerous ethnological
CDs, and sampled on albums by bands such as world music group Deep
Forest.
	   The notoriety brings new attention to the 380,000 indigenous
tribal people who make up less than 2 percent of Taiwan's
population and still face an uphill battle in mainstream society.
	   Descendants of Pacific island hoppers who migrated to Taiwan
thousands of years ago, the tribal people speak a variety
Austronesian languages similar to native tongues of the
Philippines, New Zealand and Hawaii.
	   For many, the Mandarin and Taiwanese Chinese spoken by most
people on the island are second languages.
	   Highland groups mostly held out against assimilation during 400
years of Chinese immigration to the island, until the 1980s sparked
a wave of migration to the cities where the tribal people found
work on government infrastructure projects.
	   Recent changes have had their ups and downs, says Kao
Cheng-shang, director of Taipei city's Commission for Native
Taiwanese Affairs
	   Traditional jobs in mines, on fishing boats and at construction
sites have been lost to industrial upgrading or cheaper foreign
workers, causing aboriginal incomes to lag behind those of most
Taiwanese, he says.
	   Without steady income, many urban tribal people can't afford
rent, so they live in shanty communities without electricity and
running water.
	   Life in the mountains sometimes isn't much better.
	   In Wufeng township two hours south of Taipei, Presbyterian
church social worker Chien Ching-nan says poverty, alcoholism and
low education levels have caused tribal people to miss out on much
of Taiwan's recent prosperity.
	   But music abounds in the villages, schools and dozens of tiny
churches that dot the area.
	   ``For a lot of people, a career in music or as a baseball player
offers the best chance to escape poverty,'' says Chien. ``It's
something God has given us.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-ARTS-Taiwan-Indigenous Voices; CT:i; 
