<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Dissident </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rights group: Chinese police prevent protests at dissident trial
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Police prevented dissidents from going to the
court where a labor activist accused of endangering state security
was due to be tried Sunday, a human rights group said.
	   Zhang Shanguang was to be tried in southern Hunan province's
Huaihua city reportedly on charges that he provided intelligence to
people overseas. The charge apparently relates to interviews Zhang
gave about farmers' protests to the U.S. government-funded Radio
Free Asia.
	   There was no immediate word Sunday whether the trial was going
ahead as planned. Telephone calls to court officials, Zhang's wife
and his lawyer were unanswered.
	   But Human Rights in China, a New York-based rights group, said
police in Hunan had mobilized ``a large number'' of officers to
watch dissidents at home and prevent them from going to the court
to show support for Zhang.
	   Police even watched people in Changsha, the provincial capital
300 kilometers (180 miles) to the east of Huiahua, the group said.
	   Despite the tight security, it said some people from as far away
as Beijing, 1,500 kilometers (930 miles) to the north, had given
police the slip and were in Huaihua to show support for Zhang.
	   Zhang, who earlier spent seven years in jail for labor rights
campaigning, was detained in July, following U.S. President Bill
Clinton's visit to China, as he was preparing to set up an
association to protect laid-off workers' rights.
	   His trial comes amid a crackdown that last week saw three
prominent dissidents given heavy jail terms. Xu Wenli, Qin Yongmin
and Wang Youcai were charged with endangering state security and
sentenced to 13 years, 12 years and 11 years respectively for
trying to organize the China Democracy Party.
	   Chinese leaders have declared they will destroy challengers to
Communist Party rule and have ordered law enforcers to eliminate
any threats to social stability.
	   Despite the crackdown, 274 people in more than 20 provinces and
major cities signed an open letter calling on Chinese leaders to
release Zhang, Human Rights in China said.
	   The letter was addressed to President Jiang Zemin, Premier Zhu
Rongji and Mary Robinson, the U.N.'s top human rights official who
visited China in September.
	   Zhang was charged with illegally providing intelligence to
people overseas because he told Radio Free Asia about farmers'
protests, according to the group. It said the charge was
unjustified.
	   ``If you are out to condemn somebody, you can always trump up a
charge,'' it said. 	   
</TEXT>
