w2473 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTS-US-KingoftheBs     12-26 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-US-King of the Bs,0873 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bad movies have been good to Conrad Brooks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo NY316 &QL; 
 &UR; By JOANN LOVIGLIO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HAGERSTOWN, Maryland (AP) _ He's been called the Sir John
Gielgud of bad cinema and he has the resume to back it up:
``Deathrow Gameshow,'' ``Plan 9 From Outer Space.''
	   It's a bad, bad, bad, bad world when you're Conrad Brooks, King
of the Bs. But low-budget films, featuring paper-plate flying
saucers and not-so-scary monsters, have been Brooks' livelihood for
more than four decades.
	   Born Conrad Biedrzycki in east Baltimore, he and his brother
moved to Hollywood in the late 1940s. He had no acting ambitions
but, after meeting now-infamous director Edward D. Wood Jr., he
changed his name to Brooks and wound up appearing in virtually
every film Wood directed.
	   He was Jamie, the bumbling police officer in 1959's ``Plan 9.''
He had two (yes, two) plum parts in 1953's ``Glen or Glenda?,'' a
peculiar tale about the travails of transvestitism _ something Wood
knew about.
	   ``My brother and I went into his apartment once and he was
walking around in a dress. We just figured that's Hollywood,'' says
Brooks, who recently left California to be near his family in
Maryland. ``But Eddie was a good man, bless his soul. ... He was my
mentor.''
	   In 1980, a book called ``The Golden Turkey Awards'' listed
``Plan 9'' as the worst movie ever made. It has everything: a
nonsensical plot, very unspecial effects (like tossed paper plates
doubling for UFOs), cardboard sets, bizarre dialogue and horrendous
acting. When falling star Bela Lugosi died early in the filming, a
local chiropractor was cast in the role and simply covered his face
with a cape. (Martin Landau won an Academy Award for best
supporting actor for his portrayal of Lugosi.)
	   The worst-ever distinction earned the film and Wood, who died in
1978, a new generation of devotees for whom the simply bad wasn't
good enough. And Brooks, energetic and animated at 68, revels in
his ties to the worst director and films of all time.
	   ``They also call me the low-budget John Barrymore. I love it!
And I agree,'' says Brooks. ``It tells me they've seen the movies _
that's what I want to hear.''
	   Brooks had a cameo role in 1994's ``Ed Wood,'' Tim Burton's
homage to the director with a heart of gold and a penchant for
angora. But it wasn't a comeback. Except for a dry spell in the
1960s, Brooks has been plugging away in the theater of the peculiar
all along.
	   ``Life is beautiful, kid,'' he gushes during an interview in his
ex-wife's memorabilia-filled trailer home in rural western
Maryland. ``I'm an actor; it's in me. I just do it for the love of
it. Can you believe I'm still in the movies with a mug like this?''
	   Brooks' staying power is unique in the B-movie world, says Gary
Svehla, president of Baltimore-based Midnight Marquee Press Inc., a
publisher of books about horror and sci-fi movies.
	   ``He made these films, but nobody recognized him because he'd
have a scene in a bar or as part of a crowd and was billed 25th in
the credits,'' Svehla said. ``But he's one of the few who survived
from that time, so he can talk about his work with people like Wood
and Lugosi. That's why he's still known, loved, recognized and very
important in cult films.''
	   More recently, Brooks has become an auteur of the absurd _
directing, producing and starring in a slew of straight-to-video
and limited-release films including ``Blood Slaves of the Vampire
Wolf'' and ``Misfit Patrol,'' a slapstick police comedy he predicts
``is going to be a classic.''
	   Brooks says he has appeared in 199 movies over the last half
century.
	   ``The films, to be quite honest, are not very good _ not to put
them down,'' Svehla says gingerly. ``But what they do have is
honesty and a certain charm. There's not a lot of money to make
them but there is a real love and a passion involved.''
	   Svehla says Brooks' films recall the 1950s heyday of low-budget
filmmaking _ little or no script, all-in-the-family casting and
bare-bones budgets.
	   ``It's like a breath of fresh air. No Hollywood gloss, no
special effects,'' Svehla says. ``Today ... you've got to make dlrs
50 million or it's a bomb.''
	   When he's not filming or appearing at East Coast sci-fi and
monster movie conventions, Brooks lives in Falling Waters, W.Va.,
and spends much of his time at the Hagerstown home of his ex-wife,
Ruthie, and daughter, Connie Granda. Both have starred in his films
and Mrs. Brooks has written music for several, which she willingly
plays for a visitor along with such favorites as Bobby Vinton's
``Melody of Love.''
	   Brooks is working in western Maryland on a horror movie
tentatively titled ``Jan-Gel: The Beast From the East.''
	   ``The beast is my neighbor, Dale Clukey,'' Brooks deadpans.
``Hey, you've got to keep your costs down, so you bring in
everybody you know.''
	   Spoken like a true Wood protege. Brooks says he wishes the
director, who died in poverty and obscurity, could see the
adoration his films achieved, but says he's proud to be following
in the master's footsteps.
	   ``And let me tell you, I've got plenty more in me,'' Brooks
says. ``You ain't seen nothing yet!''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-ARTS-US-King of the Bs; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
