<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-US-Commercials,0816 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Theater operators embrace big screen commercials
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MICHAEL WHITE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Business Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) _ Going out to see a movie once offered, if
nothing else, entertainment without those annoying commercials that
dominate television. Not anymore.
	   Commercials pitching products such as Levi's jeans and Nike
shoes are one of the theater industry's fastest growing businesses.
If you haven't already seen them, they're probably coming soon to a
theater near you.
	   Advertisements similar to the ones on television play on about
60 percent of the country's movie screens, and by industry
estimates, have become a dlrs 60 million business.
	   Big advertisers like BMW, Lincoln Mercury and Sony Corp. love
theaters because moviegoers, unlike TV viewers, don't turn the
channel or head for the refrigerator when the commercials start.
	   Exhibitors like them because they don't have to share the
profits from commercials with a movie studio.
	   ``I think everybody understands that it's vital to the
industry,'' said Dennis Fogarty, president and chief executive
officer of ScreenVision Cinema Network, a New York company that
distributes commercials shown on nearly 12,000 screens.
	   ``In order to go on building these beautiful multiplexes with
stadium seating and wraparound screens, exhibitors need money,'' he
said. ``They can no longer make it on just concession revenue and
film revenue.''
	   While television commercials consume up to a quarter of each
hour, movie commercials run in blocks of only two or three minutes
before the previews. Typically, they're slickly produced 90-second
spots of music and images with little talking.
	   They join two older forms of theater advertising: slides that
are shown to early birds before the theater lights go down and
radio-style ads played over the public address system.
	   Initially, theater owners were reluctant to add filmed
commercials to the lineup, fearing audiences would be annoyed. In
recent years, that reluctance has given way to enthusiasm from many
big chain operators.
	   Denver-based AMC Entertainment has even formed it own
subsidiary, National Cinema Network, to compete with ScreenVision.
	   In addition to AMC theaters, National Cinema distributes filmed
commercials, slides and audio ads to AMC competitors such as
General Cinema and Cinemark.
	   ScreenVision's business increased 300 percent during 1998, and
Fogarty said he expects similar growth during 1999. ScreenVision
limits its ad blocks to no more than three minutes. Fogarty is
convinced the audience doesn't mind, as long as the ads are
interesting.
	   That was the case among moviegoers who watched a Los Angeles
Times commercial one recent evening while waiting to see ``Star
Trek Insurrection'' at an Edwards cinema in suburban LaVerne. In
the ad, a young girl refuses to let her father videotape her
birthday party unless he promises to give her a film contract. Her
tactics, of course, are inspired by movie industry stories in the
Times.
	   ``The commercials are cool. They should put them on TV,'' said
Robby Krug, 14. ``They're funny.''
	   The commercial seemed to work for grownups, too.
	   ``I didn't mind it,'' said Sam Simmons, 40. ``I don't like
commercials as a rule, but I like commercials that are well done.''
	   National Cinema, whose filmed ads run on about 5,000 screens
weekly, also expects big growth in the coming years, but the
company's approach is more conservative. National Cinema's ad
packages run no more than two minutes. And the audience is warned
at the outset what they're about to see and how long it will last.
	   Oddly enough, the philosophy originated in part with the
reaction of National Cinema President Bob Martin when he sat down
in a Colorado theater a few years ago.
	   ``Something came on screen and I wasn't sure what it was, and it
turned out to be a commercial,'' he said. ``I felt a little bit
tricked, and I was annoyed and I didn't know how long it was going
to last. It aggravated me as a movie patron.''
	   For some exhibitors and studios, even a short block of carefully
crafted commercials is too much.
	   The Walt Disney Co. asks exhibitors not to show ads with its
movies. Ads are especially unpopular with exhibitors in the Los
Angeles area, where the influence of the movie industry is deep.
	   For example, Los Angeles-based Pacific Theaters, a fast-growing
chain with 400 screens in California and Hawaii, has resisted
filmed commercials despite the financial rewards.
	   ``We feel any kind of advertising takes away from the
experience,'' said Chan Wood, Pacific's executive vice president
and chief film buyer. ``It's a personal belief that when those
lights dim the audience wants to be entertained. We even have a
limit on the number of trailers, or coming attractions. We try to
get to the movie as soon as possible.''
</TEXT>
