</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-US-Sean Penn,0880 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sean Penn brings uncompromising passion to work
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MICHAEL FLEEMAN &QC; 
 &UR; AP Entertainment Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEVERLY HILLS, California (AP) _ As the sleazy, coke-sniffing,
self-destructive Hollywood casting agent in ``Hurlyburly,'' Sean
Penn offers the audience a dare as much as a performance.
	   ``'Hurlyburly' speaks to a lot of things that I'm most
interested in talking about as an actor,'' Penn said. ``And if it
turns out that it's something people what to listen to, then I
might find that acting is still a way to get through to people. If
not, I think I'll find myself quite discouraged in the audiences.''
	   Penn is sitting in a Beverly Hills hotel room, firing up the
latest link in a chain of cigarettes. He's ostensibly here to
promote ``Hurlyburly,'' though he'll have none of that TV
talk-show, let's-go-the-clip happy talk. Acting means too much to
him.
	   Away from the paparazzi, the 38-year-old Penn is obviously not
the Hollywood bad-boy caricature of the tabloids, and yet something
seems to simmer. Call it passion, anger, an obsessive refusal to
compromise. It's always there with Penn, popping up at the oddest
times.
	   Ask about how he chooses his roles and Penn will go on a tirade
about how ``sick and tired and angry'' he is about the films ``some
of my peers seem so anxious to do.''
	   ``You don't want to do things where for a paycheck they make you
look all pretty, put dramatic music behind the most vile aspects of
human nature, and sell an audience a dog and pony show that has
them going on the street afterwards feeling that their life is less
than anything they see in the movie,'' Penn said.
	   Lately, Penn has been cranking out movies the way he goes
through cigarettes, and it's left him out of breath. Two films are
out this Christmas, ``Hurlyburly'' and Terrence Malick's epic war
poem, ``The Thin Red Line.''
	   Both have Academy Award buzz for Penn, a nominee for ``Dead Man
Walking'' in 1996. The performances may be worlds apart, a
loquacious Hollywood lech vs. a quietly cynical soldier, though
they reflect his attention to roles with power, emotion and
complexity _ and his willingness to go against the commercial
mainstream.
	   The work has left him drained, ambivalent.
	   ``I can't say what I'm going to do _ or not going to do _ as an
actor at this point,'' he said.
	   Penn is speaking long-term. The immediate future is much more
clear: back to writing and directing, as he did with ``The Indian
Runner'' in 1991 and ``The Crossing Guard'' in 1995. A binge
writer, he pounded out a script after ``Hurlyburly,'' and he's in
discussions to direct a prison drama called ``Monsters Ball.''
	   ``I'm going to try to avoid the acting part of this business for
as long as I can,'' he said. ``I've acted in a bunch of movies this
year and last, and it kind of came as a rush in a sense. I did this
even though I knew I had only so much energy, and I was going to
burn out.''
	   Penn said his dedication to his work comes from his parents. His
mother, Eileen Ryan, is an actress (she recently appeared on the
television show ``Ally McBeal''), and his late father, Leo Penn,
was a blacklisted actor who became a prolific television director.
	   Leo Penn died in September, and Sean Penn says his father is ``a
continuing influence,'' a man who taught him the ``sober
decision-making processes that go into the craft.''
	   While his father was a Hollywood veteran, directing hundreds of
hours of television, from ``Kojak'' to ``Little House on the
Prairie,'' he left it to his sons to discover the pitfalls of the
entertainment business.
	   Certainly, Sean Penn's much-publicized battles with the
limelight, his volatile marriage to Madonna, his tangles with
photographers, speak to tough lessons outside his arts-supportive
family.
	   Penn doesn't go into any of the craziness in much detail, except
to say: ``I think the things that we look back on with any kind of
conflict about or regret is those circumstances when you
inadvertently hurt somebody or let down your work. You learn from
that.''
	   It is the darkest depths of Hollywood that Penn plumbs in
``Hurlyburly,'' the screen version of David Rabe's 1984 play. The
movie co-stars Kevin Spacey, Chazz Palminteri, Robin Wright Penn
(Penn's wife), Garry Shandling and two actresses in unexpected
performances: a very grown-up Anna Paquin as a runaway and a
decidedly un-bubbly Meg Ryan as a slutty stripper.
	   Penn hangs out with men exhibiting extremely bad behavior as he
goes on a cocaine-fueled search for some glimmer of hope and
humanity. It is a role he first played on stage 10 years ago and
said that ``what people don't like to face is that the social
content of the play has not changed a bit.''
	   ``What you always have to remember about Hollywood is it's a
town where for every dream there's desperation for the dream to be
accomplished,'' he said. ``You have a heightened level of colorful
people, a heightened level of frightened people, a lot of people
chasing their tail worrying about being found out as a fraud, a lot
of people who are feeling lucky, a lot of people who are feeling
unlucky and resentful.''
	   In short, he said, ``There's a lot on the line every day
emotionally for people here.''
</TEXT>
