<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Ice Hockey-NHL Roundup, 1st Add,0607 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST RUTHERFORD, New Jersey: in New York.
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Canadiens 2, Maple Leafs 1 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   In Toronto, Stephane Quintal scored with 4:58 remaining as the
Montreal Canadiens stopped the second-longest winless streak in
team history with a victory over the Toronto Maple Leafs.
	   The Canadiens were winless in 11 (0-6-5) skating into the game
against the Maple Leafs, and the score was tied at 1-1 with the
third period quickly disappearing when Quintal scored his
game-winner.
	   The Canadiens fell one game short of tying the longest winless
streak in franchise history, shared by the 1925-26 and 1935-36
teams.
	   Eric Weinrich also scored for the Canadiens (9-18-7). Steve
Thomas scored for the Maple Leafs (19-13-2).
 &UR; Panthers 3, Lightning 1
	   In Tampa, Florida, Sean Burke stopped 23 shots and Bill Lindsay
had two goals as Florida beat Tampa Bay, handing the Lightning
their ninth straight home loss.
	   Lindsay scored the game-winner in the second period and added an
empty-netter with 27.3 seconds left to play.
	   Burke was especially strong during the second period, when he
turned aside 14 of 15 shots. The goalie, who is 3-0 this season
against Tampa Bay while allowing just three goals, made point-blank
saves on Craig Janney, Cory Cross and Darcy Tucker.
	   Alex Selivanov scored for the Lightning.
 &UR; Penguins 2, Senators 1, OT
	   In Pittsburgh, Jaromir Jagr scored at 1:18 of overtime to lead
the Pittsburgh Penguins over the Ottawa Senators.
	   The Penguins, who had been outshot 13-1 in the third period,
remained unbeaten on home ice against Ottawa. The Senators are
0-13-3 in Pittsburgh since joining the NHL in 1992.
	   Backup goalie Peter Skudra played brilliantly, particularly in
the third period, to give the Penguins a chance to get their second
overtime win of the season.
 &UR; Flyers 3, Blackhawks 2
	   In Chicago, Eric Lindros and Eric Desjardins scored in the first
four minutes as the Philadelphia Flyers beat the Chicago Blackhawks
to extend their unbeaten streak to seven games.
	   Valeri Zelepukin also scored for the Flyers, 4-0-3 in their last
seven games.
	   With the win, the Flyers also improved their record this season
against Western Conference teams to 6-0-2 and stretched their
unbeaten streak against the Blackhawks to five games (4-0-1).
	   Doug Gilmour scored both Chicago goals _ and recorded his
1,200th NHL career point.
 &UR; Blues 4, Red Wings 3
	   In St. Louis, Scott Pellerin scored twice as the St. Louis Blues
extended Detroit's losing streak to a season-high five games.
	   The five-game losing streak is the longest for the two-time
defending Stanley Cup champions since the 1990-91 season. However,
the Red Wings have a long way to go before reaching the team record
of 14 straight losses, which took place from Feb. 24-March 25,
1982.
	   Detroit will look to snap the current slide Monday night when it
meets the Blues at Joe Louis Arena.
 &UR; Predators 3, Capitals 1
	   In Nashville, Tennessee, rookie goaltender Tomas Vokoun earned
his second straight win against a 1998 Stanley Cup finalist as the
expansion Nashville Predators knocked off the Washington Capitals.
	   Vokoun, who had made 50 saves in the Predators' 5-3 victory over
Detroit on Wednesday, needed to stop just 26 of 27 shots against
the struggling Capitals. Washington is just 3-9-0 in its last 12
games.
	   James Black's goal with 7:07 left in the game spoiled the
shutout bid of Vokoun, a 22-year-old from the Czech Republic who is
4-3-2 in relief of the injured Mike Dunham.
	   Bob Boughner, Vitali Yachmenev and Greg Johnson scored for
Nashville.
</TEXT>
