<HEADER>
w2517 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cambodia-KhmerRouge     12-26 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Khmer Rouge </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
King welcomes defections by top Khmer Rouge leaders
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ King Norodom Sihanouk has approved
the defections of two key leaders of the Khmer Rouge reign of
terror in a deal marking the death rattle of the revolutionary
group.
	   Prime Minister Hun Sen negotiated the final touches on the
defections Friday night _ the 20th anniversary of the Christmas
1978 invasion by Vietnam that toppled the genocidal regime.
	   Khieu Samphan, long the nominal Khmer Rouge leader while others
held real power, and political chief Nuon Chea said in letters to
the prime minister and king that they wished to live out the rest
of their lives as ``ordinary citizens.''
	   Hun Sen passed on the messages to the king, who is receiving
medical treatment in Beijing. Sihanouk was held prisoner in his
palace during the Khmer Rouge regime and lost a dozen family
members.
	   Sihanouk's response late Saturday echoed conciliatory language
used by Hun Sen and did not mention bringing the pair to trial for
causing the deaths of as many as 2 million Cambodians after seizing
power in 1975.
	   The king expressed ``deep gratitude about this good news'' and
praised Hun Sen's `` success in applying the Royal Government's
policy of national reconciliation to provide our people with a
complete peace and happiness and to speed national reconstruction
and progress.''
	   Hun Sen has brushed aside questions whether Khieu Samphan and
Nuon Chea would be tried by Cambodian courts or an international
tribunal, indicating a deal was struck allowing them to surrender
in exchange for not being punished.
	   The defections leave at large only one major Khmer Rouge figure,
the one-legged general Ta Mok, known as ``The Butcher.'' A Thai
army general whose troops monitor the Cambodian border estimated
that Ta Mok had no more than 100 die-hard guerrillas with him.
	   A Hun Sen aide, Om Yentieng, said Ta Mok's arrest is still
sought. But Thai Maj. Gen. Wiwat Sattarak said the Cambodian
government was more prepared to ``let him grow old and die'' in the
jungle.
	   The Cambodian government and the United States have said in the
past that they wanted Khieu Samphan, Nuon Chea and Ta Mok captured
and tried for genocide and crimes against humanity.
	   Longtime Khmer Rouge leader Pol Pot _ purged in a bloody power
struggle last year _ died of a purported heart attack in April
under house arrest by his ex-comrades.
	   A team of legal experts appointed by the United Nations visited
Cambodia last month to assess evidence for a possible international
tribunal. Local U.N. officials said the report was due to reach
Secretary-General Kofi Annan in a few weeks.
	   Om Yentieng said the prime minister supports a trial but that
justice should be left to woefully unequipped local courts.
	   Over the past two years, the government has adopted a policy of
negotiating de facto amnesty with Khmer Rouge leaders to persuade
them to end nearly two decades of stalemated civil war since they
were overthrown.
	   The strategy brought peace to large areas of Cambodia for the
first time in a generation, but means that none of the group's most
bloodstained chieftains has been arrested.
	   Khieu Samphan and Nuon Chea have surfaced in Pailin in
Cambodia's rugged northwest. The area is controlled by one of their
old comrades, Pol Pot's brother-in-law Ieng Sary, the first Khmer
Rouge leader to make peace with the government. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Cambodia-Khmer Rouge; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:AFRI;)
