<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Yachting-Sydney-Hobart </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Wild weather greets fleet
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDs: will be updated by 1300GMT with late Sunday positions &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ The fleet in the annual
Sydney-to-Hobart yacht race was encountering what the skippers
described as ``extreme'' weather as it battled its way across Bass
Strait on Sunday.
	   Race leaders Sayonara and Brindabella were encountering heavy
seas and winds of up to 45 knots as they led the fleet toward
Flinders Island, with American yacht Sayonara 3.1 nautical miles
ahead.
	   Further back in the fleet the South Australian yacht Doctor
Rager reported winds of 50 to 60 knots and gusting to 70 knots.
	   Organizers said they were the worst conditions the race had
struck since the gale-swept 1993 event.
	   The destination in the 630-nautical mile race is Hobart, capital
of the island state of Tasmania.
	   Only nine yachts in the original 115-boat fleet had retired, the
latest being the Sydney pocket maxi Innkeeper. Others out of the
race were Wild Thing, Sydney, ABN AMRO Challenge, Sledgehammer,
King Billy, Marchioness, Assassin and Red Jacket.
	   Sayonara and Brindabella remained many miles ahead of the
position reached by German maxi Morning Glory in the same time when
she set the race record of 2 days, 14 hours, seven minutes and 10
seconds in 1996. (djp) 	   
</TEXT>
